{"title_page": "Henry D. Moore Parish House and Library", "text_new": "{{Infobox NRHP\n  | name           = Henry D. Moore Parish House and Library\n  | nrhp_type      = \n  | image          = SteubenME MooreParishHouseAndLibrary.jpg\n  | caption        = \n  | location       = 22 Village Rd., [[Steuben, Maine]]\n  | coordinates    = {{coord|44|30|39|N|67|57|43|W|display=inline,title}}\n  | locmapin       = Maine#USA\n  | built          = {{Start date|1911}}\n  | architect      = Isaac Parsell\n  | architecture   = Late 19th And 20th Century Revivals\n  | added          = November 29, 2001\n  | area           = less than one acre\n  | governing_body = Private\n  | refnum         = 01001272<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''Henry D. Moore Parish House and Library''' is an historic library and community meeting hall at 22 Village Road in [[Steuben, Maine]].  Built in 1911 and enlarged in 2007, it is a notable local example of a mix of Colonial Revival and Craftsman styles, and is the only known work in Maine of [[Philadelphia]] architect Isaac Parsell.  The building was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 2001.<ref name=NRHP>{{cite web|url={{NRHP url|id=01001272}}|title=NRHP nomination for Henry D. Moore Parish House and Library|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=2015-11-21}}</ref>\n\n==Description and history==\nThe Moore Parish House and Library is located in Steuben's village center, on the south side of Village Road, between the town's triangular green and [[United States Route 1]].  It is a two-story wood frame structure, with a hip roof, clapboarded exterior, and a foundation that is part stone and part poured concrete.  It consists of an original portion, roughly five bays wide, that was built in 1911, and a two-bay extension added to the right in 2007.  The roof of the original portion has deep overhanging eaves with exposed rafter ends in the Craftsman style, and a complex pattern of window layout.  A gabled entry projects near the center of this section, with a porch supported by round columns sheltering an entry with flanking sidelight windows.  To the left of the entrance are row of stepped fixed-pane windows, marking the presence of a staircase.  The interior includes an auditorium with stage, smaller meeting spaces, and two rooms used by the local historical society, in addition to the library facilities.<ref name=NRHP/>\n\nThe original portion of the building was completed in July 1911 and publicly dedicated a month later.  The building was a gift to the town of native son Henry Dyer Moore, a businessman active in [[New York (state)|New York]] and [[New Jersey]].  It has served the town since then as its public library, and as a community meeting space.<ref name=NRHP/>  The building was enlarged in 2007 to provide additional meeting spaces and code-compliant access facilities; the architect was Sam Woodward.<ref name=hist>{{cite web|url=http://www.moorelibrary.org/about.shtml|title=About the Moore Library|publisher=Moore Library|accessdate=2015-11-21}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[National Register of Historic Places listings in Washington County, Maine]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.moorelibrary.org/ Official Site]\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Libraries on the National Register of Historic Places in Maine]]\n[[Category:Public libraries in Maine]]\n[[Category:Libraries in Washington County, Maine]]\n[[Category:Steuben, Maine]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Washington County, Maine]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox NRHP\n  | name           = Henry D. Moore Parish House and Library\n  | nrhp_type      = \n  | image          = SteubenME MooreParishHouseAndLibrary.jpg\n  | caption        = \n  | location       = 22 Village Rd., [[Steuben, Maine]]\n  | coordinates    = {{coord|44|30|39|N|67|57|43|W|display=inline,title}}\n  | locmapin       = Maine#USA\n  | built          = {{Start date|1911}}\n  | architect      = Isaac Parsell\n  | architecture   = Late 19th And 20th Century Revivals\n  | added          = November 29, 2001\n  | area           = less than one acre\n  | governing_body = Private\n  | refnum         = 01001272<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''Henry D. Moore Parish House and Library''' is an historic library and community meeting hall at 22 Village Road in [[Steuben, Maine]].  Built in 1911 and enlarged in 2007, it is a notable local example of a mix of Colonial Revival and Craftsman styles, and is the only known work in Maine of [[Philadelphia]] architect Isaac Parsell.  The building was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 2001.<ref name=NRHP>{{cite web|url={{NRHP url|id=01001272}}|title=NRHP nomination for Henry D. Moore Parish House and Library|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=2015-11-21}}</ref>\n\n==Description and history==\nThe Moore Parish House and Library is located in Steuben's village center, on the south side of Village Road, between the town's triangular green and [[United States Route 1]].  It is a two-story wood frame structure, with a hip roof, clapboarded exterior, and a foundation that is part stone and part poured concrete.  It consists of an original portion, roughly five bays wide, that was built in 1911, and a two-bay extension added to the right in 2007.  The roof of the original portion has deep overhanging eaves with exposed rafter ends in the Craftsman style, and a complex pattern of window layout.  A gabled entry projects near the center of this section, with a porch supported by round columns sheltering an entry with flanking sidelight windows.  To the left of the entrance are row of stepped fixed-pane windows, marking the presence of a staircase.  The interior includes an auditorium with stage, smaller meeting spaces, and two rooms used by the local historical society, in addition to the library facilities.<ref name=NRHP/>\n\nThe original portion of the building was completed in July 1911 and publicly dedicated a month later.  The building was a gift to the town of native son Henry Dyer Moore, a businessman active in [[New York (state)|New York]] and [[New Jersey]].  It has served the town since then as its public library, and as a community meeting space.<ref name=NRHP/>  The building was enlarged in 2007 to provide additional meeting spaces and code-compliant access facilities; the architect was Sam Woodward.<ref name=hist>{{cite web|url=http://www.moorelibrary.org/about.shtml|title=About the Moore Library|publisher=Moore Library|accessdate=2015-11-21}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[National Register of Historic Places listings in Washington County, Maine]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.moorelibrary.org/ Official Site]\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places}}\n\n[[Category:Libraries on the National Register of Historic Places in Maine]]\n[[Category:Public libraries in Maine]]\n[[Category:Libraries in Washington County, Maine]]\n[[Category:Steuben, Maine]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Washington County, Maine]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_D._Moore_Parish_House_and_Library"}
{"title_page": "Vishwanath Meghwal", "text_new": "{{moresources|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Vishwanath Meghwal\n| image =\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1966|4|6|df=y}}\n| birth_place = Ratannagar, [[Churu district|Churu]], Rajasthan\n| office = Parliamentary Secretary, [[Government of Rajasthan]]\n| term = 2014 - 2018\n| office2 = Member of the [[Rajasthan Legislative Assembly]]\n| term2 = 2013 - 2018\n| constituency2 = Khajuwala\n| spouse = Vimla\n| children = 2\n| party = [[Bharatiya Janata Party]]\n| nationality = [[Indian people|Indian]]\n}}\n\n'''Vishwanath Meghwal''' is an Indian politician and current Member of the [[Rajasthan Legislative Assembly]] from Khajuwala [[Bikaner district]] in [[Rajasthan]]. He is a [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] politician.<ref>[http://www.rajassembly.nic.in/MembersPage.asp?DivNo=162 Dr. Vishwanath Meghwal MLA bio profile]</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Meghwal, Vishwanath}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Rajasthani politicians]]\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{moresources|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Vishwanath Meghwal\n| image =\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1966|4|6|df=y}}\n| birth_place = Ratannagar, [[Churu]], Rajasthan\n| office = Parliamentary Secretary, [[Government of Rajasthan]]\n| term = 2014 - 2018\n| office2 = Member of the [[Rajasthan Legislative Assembly]]\n| term2 = 2013 - 2018\n| constituency2 = Khajuwala\n| spouse = Vimla\n| children = 2\n| party = [[Bharatiya Janata Party]]\n| nationality = [[Indian people|Indian]]\n}}\n\n'''Vishwanath Meghwal''' is an Indian politician and current Member of the [[Rajasthan Legislative Assembly]] from Khajuwala [[Bikaner district]] in [[Rajasthan]]. He is a [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] politician.<ref>[http://www.rajassembly.nic.in/MembersPage.asp?DivNo=162 Dr. Vishwanath Meghwal MLA bio profile]</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Meghwal, Vishwanath}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Rajasthani politicians]]\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n", "name_user": "Paradoctor", "label": "safe", "comment": "dab", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vishwanath_Meghwal"}
{"title_page": "Henry County Library System", "text_new": "{{Infobox library\n| name = Henry County Library System\n| name_en = <!-- Name in English if different -->\n| logo = File:Henry_County_Library_System.png\n| logo_size = 250\n| logo_alt = \n| image = <!-- file name only (no Image: or File:) -->\n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| country = USA\n| type = \n| scope = \n| established = \n| dissolved = \n| ref_legal_mandate = \n| location = Henry County, Georgia\n| coordinates = \n| branch_of = \n| num_branches = 5\n| items_collected = \n| collection_size = 286,466 (2016)<ref name=\"GALib16\" />\n| criteria = \n| legal_deposit = \n| req_to_access = \n| annual_circulation = 413,004 (2016)<ref name=\"GALib16\" />\n| pop_served = 233,916 (2016)<ref name=\"GALib16\" />\n| members = 70,793 (2016)<ref name=\"GALib16\">{{cite web|title=A Current Look at Georgia Libraries 2016|url=http://www.georgialibraries.org/lib/publiclibinfo/currentlook/Current_Look_FY-16.pdf|accessdate=3 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170308045215/http://www.georgialibraries.org/lib/publiclibinfo/currentlook/Current_Look_FY-16.pdf|archive-date=8 March 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| budget = \n| director = Kathryn E. Pillatzki\n| num_employees = \n| website = http://www.henrylibraries.org\n| references = \n| embed = \n| module = \n}}\n{{Coord|33.442923|-84.127341|display=title}}\nThe '''Henry County Library System (HCLS)''' is a [[public library]] system consisting of five branches in [[Henry County, Georgia]]. The five branches are located in the towns of [[Stockbridge, Georgia|Stockbridge]], [[Hampton, Georgia|Hampton]], [[Locust Grove, Georgia|Locust Grove]], and [[McDonough, Georgia|McDonough]].\n\nHCLS is a member of [[Public Information Network for Electronic Services|PINES]], a program of the [[Georgia Public Library Service]] that covers 53 library systems in 143 counties of Georgia.<ref>{{cite web|title=PINES - About|url=http://pines.georgialibraries.org/about|accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref> Any resident in a PINES supported library system has access to over 10.6 million books in the system's circulation.<ref>{{cite web|title=PINES Facts|url=http://pines.georgialibraries.org/sites/default/files/files/PINES_Facts_2016.pdf|accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref> The library is also serviced by GALILEO, a program of the University System of Georgia which stands for \"GeorgiA LIbrary LEarning Online\". This program offers residents in supported libraries access to over 100 databases indexing thousands of periodicals and scholarly journals. It also boasts over 10,000 journal titles in full text.<ref>{{cite web|title=GALILEO - About|url=http://about.galileo.usg.edu/|accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe library also has an agreement with [[Gordon State College]] to combine resources to better serve the students at the school. The McDonough branch additionally allows access to classroom space, computers, and other resource assistance on an as needed basis for the students.<ref>{{cite web|title=HENRY COUNTY LIBRARY SYSTEM, GORDON STATE AT MCDONOUGH SIGN AGREEMENT|url=http://www.gordonstate.edu/newsroom/view/henry-county-library-system-gordon-state-at-mcdonough-sign-agreement|website=Gordan State College|accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Henry County Developmental Authority|url=http://www.choosehenry.com/Henry/media/Henry/Secondary%20Pages/Downloads/Nov-6-2014-Approved-Meeting-Minutes-with-Staff-Reports.pdf?ext=.pdf|website=Choose Henry|accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Branches==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Address \n|-\n| Cochran Public Library  || 174 Burke St, Stockbridge, GA 30281\n|-\n| Fairview Public Library || 28 Austin Rd, Stockbridge, GA 30281\n|-\n| Fortson Public Library || 61 McDonough St, Hampton, GA 30228\n|-\n| Locust Grove Public Library || 115 Martin Luther King Jr Blvd, Locust Grove, GA 30248\n|-\n| McDonough Public Library || 1001 Florence McGarity Blvd, McDonough, GA 30252\n|-\n|}\n