{"title_page": "E v Secretary of State for the Home Department", "text_new": "{{short description|Landmark case of 2004 developing error of fact as a distinct ground for judicial review}}\n{{italic title|all=yes}}\n\n{{Infobox court case\n|name               = E v Secretary of State for the Home Department\n|court              = [[Court of Appeal (England and Wales)|Court of Appeal (Civil Div.)]]\n|image = Royal courts of justice.jpg\n|imagesize = 250px\n|caption =  \n|full name          = \"E\"&nbsp;\u2013&nbsp;and&nbsp;\u2013&nbsp;Secretary of State for the Home Department\n|date decided       = {{start date|2004|02|02|df=}} \n|citations          = {{cite BAILII|litigants= E v Secretary of State for the Home Department |link= E v Secretary of State for the Home Department|court = EWCA|division =Civ|year=2004|num=49|para=|parallelcite=[2004] EWCA Civ 49|date=2 February 2004|courtname=auto}}\n|ECLI               = \n|transcripts        = \n|judges             = [[Lord Phillips of Worth Matravers]]<BR>[[Charles Mantell|Lord Justice Mantell]]<BR>[[Robert Carnwath, Lord Carnwath of Notting Hill|Lord Justice Carnwath]]\n|number of judges   = 3\n|decision by        = \n|concurring         = \n|dissenting         = \n|concur/dissent     = \n|prior actions      = \n|appealed from      = [[Asylum and Immigration Tribunal|Immigration Appeal Tribunal]]\n|appealed to        = \n|subsequent actions = \n|related actions    = \n|opinions           =  Whether new evidence, if admitted, would demonstrate an error of law;<BR>New evidence produced after the hearing but before the decision date;<BR>Failure to consider new evidence in the context of the power to direct a rehearing\n|keywords           = {{hlist|New evidence |Mistake of fact|<BR>Statutory appeal on point of law|Power to reopen|Unfairness|Immigration and Asylum}}\n|italic title       = E v Secretary of State for the Home Department\n}}\n\n'''''E v Secretary of State for the Home Department''''' was a landmark judicial review appeal of 2004 which significantly developed the doctrine of ''error of fact'' as a distinct ground which was taken in conjunction with the question of new evidence (or the most recent decision) being considered in order to establish the error.<ref name=\"Bailii1\">{{cite court | litigants = E v Secretary of State for the Home Department|vol=49 |reporter=QB |opinion=1044 ||court=EWCA (Civ) |date=2004 |url = https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWCA/Civ/2004/49.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://swarb.co.uk/e-v-secretary-of-state-for-the-home-department-etc-ca-2-feb-2004/ |title=E v Secretary of State for the Home Department: CA 2 Feb 2004  |last=Swarbrick |first=David |date= 7 April 2019 |website=Swarb.co.uk |access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> The case laid out in definitive terms the criteria for the court to review a finding of ''mistake of fact'' leading to unfairness.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Fordham |first1=Michael |date=July 2012 |chapter=<P49.2.2> |title=Judicial Review Handbook |edition=Sixth |location=Oxford |publisher=Hart Publishing Ltd. |page=510 |isbn=9781849461597 |quote=''(...considering error of fact as a ground of appeal for \u2033error of law\u2033)''}}</ref><ref>{{cite court | litigants = E v Secretary of State for the Home Department|vol=49 |reporter=QB |opinion=1044 |pinpoint=66|court=EWCA (Civ) |date=2004 |url = https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWCA/Civ/2004/49.html|quote=''In our view, the time has now come to accept that a mistake of fact giving rise to unfairness is a separate head of challenge in an appeal on a point of law...''}}</ref> In establishing an error of fact according to the requirements, a duty was identified to consider a decision; in particular, the duty to reopen a matter or direct a rehearing.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Fordham |first1=Michael |date=July 2012 |chapter=<6.1.7> |title=Judicial Review Handbook |edition=Sixth |location=Oxford |publisher=Hart Publishing Ltd. |page=66 |isbn=9781849461597 |quote=''...discussing IAT\u2032s power to direct a rehearing.''}}</ref> The question of new evidence produced after the hearing but before the decision date was considered within the context of the power of the [[Immigration Appellate Authority|Immigration Appeal Tribunal]] (IAT) to direct a rehearing.<ref name=\"HerbertSmith1\">{{cite web |url= https://www.lexology.com/library/document.ashx?g=eb768e10-170d-40ea-8fa0-eea78c52d871 |title= Challenging a decision for mistake of fact|last1= Lidbetter |first1= Andrew |last2= Zar |first2= Nusrat |last3= Condliffe |first3=Anna |publisher= Herbert Smith Freehills LLP|date=19 November 2009 |website=www.lexology.com |access-date=2020-04-20 |quote=''It has been clear since the Court of Appeal\u2032s decision in E v Secretary of State for the Home Department [2004] EWCA Civ 49 that mistake of fact giving rise to unfairness can be a separate head of challenge.''}}</ref>\n\n==Facts==\nTwo appellants, who had separately claimed [[Right of asylum|asylum]] in the United Kingdom, were heard jointly in the Court of Appeal. They were known only as \u2032E\u2032 and \u2032R\u2032.\n\n\u2032E\u2032 was an Egyptian national who came to the UK from [[Bangladesh]] in April 2001 and claimed asylum. \u2032E\u2032 was considered to be sympathetic to the [[Muslim Brotherhood]], particularly since his father was a member of the society.\n\n\u2032R\u2032 was an Afghan national who came to the UK in August 2001 and claimed asylum. The grounds for asylum were that \u2032R\u2032 had converted from [[Islam]] to [[Christianity]] and if made to return would most likely be subject to severe persecution. The Tribunal (IAT) rejected the appeal of \u2032R\u2032, even though the evidence per se was not in dispute. \u2032R\u2032 applied to the Court of Appeal for permission to appeal on 1st September 2003. New evidence, in the form of an additional CIPU (Country Information and Policy Unit) report of April 2003 was put forward to help substantiate the seriousness of the risk of persecution. Anyone suspected or even accused of conversion to Christianity could face severe punishment and in all likelihood, could be put to death. Permission to appeal was refused by the IAT.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.casemine.com/judgement/uk/5a8ff7b260d03e7f57eb14a6 |title=E v Secretary of State for Home Department [2004] EWCA Civ 49 |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=2 February 2004 |website=Casemine |access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[R (March) v Secretary of State for Health]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Law-stub}}\n\n[[Category:Public law]]\n[[Category:Common law]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom public law]]\n[[Category:Law of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Judicial review]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Landmark case of 2004 developing error of fact as a distinct ground for judicial review}}\n{{italic title|all=yes}}\n\n{{Infobox court case\n|name               = E v Secretary of State for the Home Department\n|court              = [[Court of Appeal (England and Wales)|Court of Appeal (Civil Div.)]]\n|image = Royal courts of justice.jpg\n|imagesize = 250px\n|caption =  \n|full name          = \"E\"&nbsp;\u2013&nbsp;and&nbsp;\u2013&nbsp;Secretary of State for the Home Department\n|date decided       = {{start date|2004|02|02|df=}} \n|citations          = {{cite BAILII|litigants= E v Secretary of State for the Home Department |link= E v Secretary of State for the Home Department|court = EWCA|division =Civ|year=2004|num=49|para=|parallelcite=[2004] EWCA Civ 49|date=2 February 2004|courtname=auto}}\n|ECLI               = \n|transcripts        = \n|judges             = [[Lord Phillips of Worth Matravers]]<BR>[[Charles Mantell|Lord Justice Mantell]]<BR>[[Robert Carnwath, Lord Carnwath of Notting Hill|Lord Justice Carnwath]]\n|number of judges   = 3\n|decision by        = \n|concurring         = \n|dissenting         = \n|concur/dissent     = \n|prior actions      = \n|appealed from      = [[Asylum and Immigration Tribunal|Immigration Appeal Tribunal]]\n|appealed to        = \n|subsequent actions = \n|related actions    = \n|opinions           =  Whether new evidence, if admitted, would demonstrate an error of law;<BR>New evidence produced after the hearing but before the decision date;<BR>Failure to consider new evidence in the context of the power to direct a rehearing\n|keywords           = {{hlist|New evidence |Mistake of fact|<BR>Statutory appeal on point of law|Power to reopen|Unfairness|Immigration and Asylum}}\n|italic title       = E v Secretary of State for the Home Department\n}}\n\n'''''E v Secretary of State for the Home Department''''' was a landmark judicial review appeal of 2004 which significantly developed the doctrine of ''error of fact'' as a distinct ground which was taken in conjunction with the question of new evidence (or the most recent decision) being considered in order to establish the error.<ref name=\"Bailii1\">{{cite court | litigants = E v Secretary of State for the Home Department|vol=49 |reporter=QB |opinion=1044 ||court=EWCA (Civ) |date=2004 |url = https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWCA/Civ/2004/49.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://swarb.co.uk/e-v-secretary-of-state-for-the-home-department-etc-ca-2-feb-2004/ |title=E v Secretary of State for the Home Department: CA 2 Feb 2004  |last=Swarbrick |first=David |date= 7 April 2019 |website=Swarb.co.uk |access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> The case laid out in definitive terms the criteria for the court to review a finding of ''mistake of fact'' leading to unfairness.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Fordham |first1=Michael |date=July 2012 |chapter=<P49.2.2> |title=Judicial Review Handbook |edition=Sixth |location=Oxford |publisher=Hart Publishing Ltd. |page=510 |isbn=9781849461597 |quote=''(...considering error of fact as a ground of appeal for \u2033error of law\u2033)''}}</ref><ref>{{cite court | litigants = E v Secretary of State for the Home Department|vol=49 |reporter=QB |opinion=1044 |pinpoint=66|court=EWCA (Civ) |date=2004 |url = https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWCA/Civ/2004/49.html|quote=''In our view, the time has now come to accept that a mistake of fact giving rise to unfairness is a separate head of challenge in an appeal on a point of law...''}}</ref> In establishing an error of fact according to the requirements, a duty was identified to consider a decision; in particular, the duty to reopen a matter or direct a rehearing.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Fordham |first1=Michael |date=July 2012 |chapter=<6.1.7> |title=Judicial Review Handbook |edition=Sixth |location=Oxford |publisher=Hart Publishing Ltd. |page=66 |isbn=9781849461597 |quote=''...discussing IAT\u2032s power to direct a rehearing.''}}</ref> The question of new evidence produced after the hearing but before the decision date was considered within the context of the power of the [[Immigration Appellate Authority|Immigration Appeal Tribunal]] (IAT) to direct a rehearing.<ref name=\"HerbertSmith1\">{{cite web |url= https://www.lexology.com/library/document.ashx?g=eb768e10-170d-40ea-8fa0-eea78c52d871 |title= Challenging a decision for mistake of fact|last1= Lidbetter |first1= Andrew |last2= Zar |first2= Nusrat |last3= Condliffe |first3=Anna |publisher= Herbert Smith Freehills LLP|date=19 November 2009 |website=www.lexology.com |access-date=2020-04-20 |quote=''It has been clear since the Court of Appeal\u2032s decision in E v Secretary of State for the Home Department [2004] EWCA Civ 49 that mistake of fact giving rise to unfairness can be a separate head of challenge.''}}</ref>\n\n==Facts==\nTwo appellants, who had separately claimed [[Right of asylum|asylum]] in the United Kingdom, were heard jointly in the Court of Appeal. They were known only as \u2032E\u2032 and \u2032R\u2032.\n\n\u2032E\u2032 was an Egyptian national who came to the UK from [[Bangladesh]] in April 2001 and claimed asylum. \u2032E\u2032 was considered to be sympathetic to the [[Muslim Brotherhood]], particularly since his father was a member of the society.\n\n\u2032R\u2032 was an Afghan national who came to the UK in August 2001 and claimed asylum. The grounds for asylum were that \u2032R\u2032 had converted from [[Islam]] to [[Christianity]] and if made to return would most likely be subject to severe persecution. The Tribunal (IAT) rejected the appeal of \u2032R\u2032, even though the evidence per se was not in dispute. \u2032R\u2032 applied to the Court of Appeal for permission to appeal on 1st September 2003. New evidence, in the form of an additional CIPU (Country Information and Policy Unit) report of April 2003 was put forward to help substantiate the seriousness of the risk of persecution. Anyone suspected or even accused of conversion to Christianity could face severe punishment and in all likelihood, could be put to death. Permission to appeal was refused by the IAT.\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[R (March) v Secretary of State for Health]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Law-stub}}\n\n[[Category:Public law]]\n[[Category:Common law]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom public law]]\n[[Category:Law of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Judicial review]]\n", "name_user": "SpookiePuppy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFacts:Adding reference.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E_v_Secretary_of_State_for_the_Home_Department"}
{"title_page": "Gun laws in Pennsylvania", "text_new": "[[File:Map of USA PA.svg |thumb|Location of Pennsylvania in the United States]]\n'''Gun laws in Pennsylvania''' regulate the sale, possession, and use of [[firearm]]s and [[ammunition]] in the [[Commonwealth (U.S. state)|Commonwealth]] of [[Pennsylvania]] in the United States.<ref name=LCAV-PA>[http://smartgunlaws.org/pennsylvania-state-law-summary/ \"Pennsylvania State Law Summary\"], Law Center to Prevent Gun Violence. Retrieved January 2, 2013.</ref><ref name=NRA-ILA-PA>[https://www.nraila.org/gun-laws/state-gun-laws/pennsylvania/ \"State Gun Laws: Pennsylvania\"], National Rifle Association \u2013 Institute for Legislative Action. Retrieved December 27, 2015.</ref><ref name=batfe-book-2007>{{cite web |url=http://www.atf.gov/publications/download/p/atf-p-5300-5.pdf |title=Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms, and Explosives \u2013 State Laws and Published Ordinances \u2013 Firearms |accessdate=January 2, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111109215323/http://www.atf.gov/publications/download/p/atf-p-5300-5.pdf |archive-date=November 9, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Summary table==\n<!-- Transcludes to [[Gun laws in the United States (by state)]] --><onlyinclude>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"font-size:85%; width:95%;\"\n|-\n! Subject/Law !! Long guns!! Handguns !! Relevant statutes !! Notes\n|-\n| State permit required to purchase? || No || No ||||\n|-\n| Firearm registration? || No || Partial || [http://www.legis.state.pa.us/cfdocs/legis/LI/consCheck.cfm?txtType=HTM&ttl=18&div=0&chpt=61 18 Pa.C.S. \u00a7 6111.4] || 18 Pa.C.S. \u00a7 6111.4 forbids the government from creating a firearm registry. Nevertheless, all handgun buyers in the state must undergo a PICS check at the point of sale, a record of which is maintained by the state police in a \"sales database\". The [[Pennsylvania Supreme Court]] has ruled that this is legal under the aforementioned statue, as it is not a comprehensive record of all handgun ownership within the state \u2014 gun owners moving into the state are not required to register their firearms.\n|-\n| Assault weapon law? || No || No || ||\n|-\n| Owner license required? || No || No || || \n|-\n| License required for concealed carry? || N/A || Yes || [http://www.legis.state.pa.us/WU01/LI/LI/CT/HTM/18/00.061..HTM 18 Pa.C.S. \u00a7 6109] || License to Carry Firearms issued on a \"shall-issue\" basis. A LTCF is required to carry a firearm concealed on one's person, in a vehicle, or during a declared state of emergency.\n|-\n| License required for open carry? || No || No || || Unlicensed open-carry, except license required in Philadelphia (City of the First Class) and when within a vehicle.\nOn May 31, 2019, the [[Supreme Court of Pennsylvania|Pennsylvania Supreme Court]] ruled that carrying a firearm is not reasonable suspicion to detain someone.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.princelaw.com/2019/05/31/monumental-decision-from-the-pennsylvania-supreme-court-regarding-whether-the-open-carrying-of-a-firearm-is-reasonable-suspicion-of-a-crime/|title=MONUMENTAL Decision from the Pennsylvania Supreme Court regarding whether the Open Carrying of a Firearm is Reasonable Suspicion of a Crime|last=Prince|first=Joshua|last2=Esq.|date=2019-05-31|website=Prince Law Offices Blog|language=en|access-date=2019-05-31}}</ref>\n|-\n| Castle Law/Stand Your Ground? || Yes || Yes || [http://www.legis.state.pa.us/CFDOCS/Legis/PN/Public/btCheck.cfm?txtType=HTM&sessYr=2011&sessInd=0&billBody=H&billTyp=B&billNbr=0040] || Castle Law. No duty to retreat inside castle. No duty to retreat outside castle if confronted with a deadly weapon or an object that appears to be one in a place where the person has a right to be.\n|-\n| State preemption of local restrictions? || Yes || Yes || [http://www.legis.state.pa.us/WU01/LI/LI/CT/HTM/18/00.061..HTM 18 Pa.C.S. \u00a7 6120] ||\n|-\n| [[National Firearms Act|NFA]] weapons restricted? || No || No || ||\n|-\n| Peaceable Journey laws? || Yes || Yes || [http://www.psp.pa.gov/firearms-information/Pages/Carrying-Firearms-in-Pennsylvania.aspx#.VOuuQy7e8rc] || Non-residents may carry in a vehicle if in possession of a valid carry permit from any state. Otherwise, federal rules observed.\n|-\n| Background checks required for private sales? || No || Yes || || All private party transfers of handguns must be processed through a licensed dealer, or at a county sheriff's office. In either case a background check is required.\n|}</onlyinclude>\n\n== State gun legislation==\n\n=== Act 192 of 2014 ===\nAct 192 of 2014 allowed gun owners and firearm advocacy groups to file suit against local municipalities for their gun control ordinances.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/pennsylvania-court-law-nra-gun-challenges/|title=Court tosses Pennsylvania law aiding NRA gun challenges|access-date=2018-04-25|language=en}}</ref> Philadelphia, Lancaster, Pittsburgh and five democratic legislators filed suit on the grounds that the act was unconstitutional.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.phillymag.com/news/2016/06/21/pa-supreme-court-rules-nra-backed-law-unconstitutional/|title=Pa Supreme Court Rules NRA-backed Law Unconstitutional|date=2016-06-21|work=Philadelphia Magazine|access-date=2018-04-25|language=en-US}}</ref> The Pennsylvania Supreme Court ruled in favor of the cities and five legislator that the act was unconstitutional on the grounds that bills must pertain to one subject. Act 192 of 2014 was originally intended to criminalize the theft of metals.The firearm part of the act was a provision. City Solicitor Sozi Tulante released a statement against the bill: \"Act 192 was passed by the General Assembly without any public notice or debate, and would have flooded the courts with advocacy litigation even when the plaintiffs had no real legal stake in the case.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.phillymag.com/news/2016/06/21/pa-supreme-court-rules-nra-backed-law-unconstitutional/|title=Pa Supreme Court Rules NRA-backed Law Unconstitutional|date=2016-06-21|work=Philadelphia Magazine|access-date=2018-04-04|language=en-US}}</ref> Senator Daylin Leach, one of the five democrats to file suite stated: \"municipalities that repealed ordinances may now restore them\" During the case they found the law unconstitutional Justice David N. Wecht said \"If, by brute force, the majority of the General Assembly can cram through any number of regulations.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.philly.com/philly/news/politics/20160310_Pa__justices_question_roots_of_NRA-friendly_law.html|title=Pa. justices question roots of NRA-backed law - Philly|work=Philly.com|access-date=2018-04-04}}</ref>\n\n=== House Bill 170 of 2017 ===\nHouse Bill 170, introduced by Rick Saccone removed the requirement of obtaining a license in the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania to be able to legally conceal a firearm.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.yorkdispatch.com/story/news/politics/2017/10/09/constitutional-carry-pennsylvania-challenged-gun-control-advocates/735599001/|title='Constitutional carry' in Pennsylvania challenged by gun control advocates|work=York Dispatch|access-date=2018-04-25|language=en}}</ref> The Commonwealth has no requirement to be licensed to carry a firearm openly. Saccone stated \"If a citizen passes a criminal background check to purchase a new firearm, it is patently unjust and unconstitutionally questionable to add layers of bureaucratic regulations on those who are least likely to commit a crime just because the citizen prefers to carry his weapon concealed.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.yorkdispatch.com/story/news/politics/2017/10/09/constitutional-carry-pennsylvania-challenged-gun-control-advocates/735599001/|title='Constitutional carry' in Pennsylvania challenged by gun control advocates|work=York Dispatch|access-date=2018-03-27|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Senate Bill 383 of 2017 ===\nSenate Bill 383 gives school boards the authority to establish policies and protocols to allow staff members to carry concealed firearms on school property.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://fox43.com/2017/06/28/pa-senate-passes-bill-clearing-way-for-schools-to-allow-employees-guns-on-campus-with/|title=Pa. Senate passes bill clearing way for schools to allow employees' guns on campus|date=2017-06-28|work=WPMT FOX43|access-date=2018-04-25|language=en-US}}</ref> There is no mandated school participation. Staff members choosing to carry concealed firearms must do so legally.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://fox43.com/2017/06/28/pa-senate-passes-bill-clearing-way-for-schools-to-allow-employees-guns-on-campus-with/|title=Pa. Senate passes bill clearing way for schools to allow employees' guns on campus|date=2017-06-28|work=WPMT FOX43|access-date=2018-04-25|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== House Bill 921 of 2014 ===\nAuthored by rep. Timothy Krieger, the intent of the bill was to eliminate the Pennsylvania Instant Check System in favor of the National Instant Check System and allowing the Federal government to administer the background check instead of state police.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pennlive.com/midstate/index.ssf/2014/03/gun_background_check_bill_penn.html|title=Bill to eliminate Pa. background checks for gun buyers on hold until questions about national system resolved|work=PennLive.com|access-date=2018-04-25|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== House Bill 501 of 2017 ===\nLegislation to remove the second amendment rights of known domestic abusers while removing the ability to surrender their weapons to a third party and replacing the 60 days waiting period with a 24 hour order to surrender their firearms. Senator Thomas Killon's sponsorship memo stated \"The intent of this change in law is to enhance safety for parties and their children in domestic violations and protection from abuse situations. Enhancing their safety during these difficult times helps not only these families but also law enforcement charged with overall public safety.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.legis.state.pa.us/cfdocs/Legis/CSM/showMemoPublic.cfm?chamber=S&SPick=20170&cosponId=21693|title=Senate Co-Sponsorship Memoranda|last=Center|first=Legislativate Data Processing|website=The official website for the Pennsylvania General Assembly.|language=en|access-date=2018-04-04}}</ref> Governor Tom Wolf also supported the bill, stating on its behalf \" we must protect victims, spouses, and children of domestic violence and attempt to prevent domestic abusers from escalating their violence in everyday places that result in mass murder.\" \"It is time for the General Assembly to act on this bipartisan, commonsense legislation to protect victims and reduce violence.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.governor.pa.gov/wolf-calls-passage-bipartisan-enhanced-firearm-prohibition-domestic-abusers/|title=Gov. Wolf Calls for Enhanced Firearm Prohibition for Domestic Abusers|date=2017-11-13|work=Governor Tom Wolf|access-date=2018-04-04|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Local legislation and preemption==\n\n=== ''Ortiz v. Commonwealth'' ===\nIn 1993, two [[Home Rule Municipality (Pennsylvania)|Home Rule Municipalities]], [[Philadelphia]] and [[Pittsburgh]], attempted to regulate [[Assault weapon|assault weapons]]. On June 17, 1993, the [[mayor of Philadelphia]] [[Ed Rendell]] signed and approved Bill No. 508 submitted by the [[Philadelphia City Council]], which banned certain types of [[Assault weapon|assault weapons]] in [[Philadelphia County]]. In 1994, the [[Pittsburgh City Council]] passed Ordinance 30-1994, which also banned certain specified assault weapons within Pittsburgh's physical boundaries. These ordinances planned to regulate the ownership, use, possession or transfer of certain firearms. After these ordinances were enacted the [[Pennsylvania General Assembly|General Assembly]] passed House Bill 185 on October 4, 1994, which amended Title 18 of the Crimes Code, including the Pennsylvania [[Uniform Firearms Act]], 18 Pa.C.S. \u00a7\u00a7 6101-6124. The amendment, which appears at 18 Pa.C.S. \u00a7 6120, provided that no county, municipality or township could regulate the ownership or transfer of firearms or ammunition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.legis.state.pa.us/WU01/LI/LI/CT/HTM/18/00.061.020.000..HTM|title=Section 6120 - Title 18 - CRIMES AND OFFENSES|website=www.legis.state.pa.us|access-date=2019-06-02}}</ref>\n\nCouncilman Angel Ortiz of [[Philadelphia City Council]] and other Philadelphia appellants brought an action against the state in the [[Commonwealth Court of Pennsylvania]], arguing that the state had exceeded its jurisdiction over the Home Rule Municipalities in this case. The Philadelphia appellants argued that only in Philadelphia must a person obtain a license for carrying any firearm, on a public street or public property, regardless of whether it is unconcealed or concealed. Throughout the rest of Pennsylvania, a license is only necessary if one is carrying a [[Concealed carry in the United States|concealed firearm]] or is carrying one in a vehicle. 18 Pa.C.S.A. 6106(a).\n\nIn 1996, the [[Supreme Court of Pennsylvania|Pennsylvania Supreme Court]] ruled that the state preemption statute was valid and that Philadelphia and Pittsburgh could not enact stricter gun control laws.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lawcenter.giffords.org/local-authority-to-regulate-firearms-in-pennsylvania/|title=Local Authority to Regulate Firearms in Pennsylvania|date=2018-10-23|website=Giffords Law Center to Prevent Gun Violence|language=en|access-date=2019-06-02}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2008/03/06/controlling-guns-in-philadelphia|title=Controlling Guns in Philadelphia}}</ref>\n\n=== Further attempts ===\nIn 2008, [[Philadelphia]] had seven different 2007 ordinances invalidated in ''Clarke v. House of Representatives''; they included a limit of 1 handgun purchase per month and prohibiting straw purchases, reporting lost or stolen firearms, license requirement to acquire firearm or to bring one into the city, annual gun license renewal, firearm confiscation from someone posing a risk of harm, banning possession or transfer of assault rifles, and reporting requirements for ammunition sales.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://blog.princelaw.com/2015/01/16/press-release-lawsuit-filed-against-city-of-harrisburg-regarding-its-illegal-firearm-and-ammunition-ordinances/|title=PRESS RELEASE: Lawsuit Filed Against City of Harrisburg Regarding Its Illegal Firearm and Ammunition Ordinances|last=Offices|first=Prince Law|last2=P.C.|date=2015-01-16|website=Prince Law Offices Blog|language=en|access-date=2019-09-13}}</ref> In April 2008, the city sought to reenact the ordinances with minor changes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/sites/default/files/federalistsociety_pennsylvaniawhitepaperfinal_0.pdf|title=Key Issues for Pennsylvanians: What Is at Stake with the Pennsylvania Supreme Court|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The [[Philadelphia City Council]] proposed in 2016 to mandate all firearm owners with minors living in their custody lock their firearms at all times. The firearms must also be in a locked area with ammunition also being in a locked area; separate from the firearm.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gambonelaw.com/blog/can-philly-pass-its-own-gun-control-law-.cfm|title=The Problem with Philadelphia's Gun Control Proposal|work=Gambone Law|access-date=2018-04-04|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.guns.com/news/2016/06/06/philadelphia-moves-to-mandate-gun-lock-use|title=Philadelphia moves to mandate gun lock use|date=2016-06-06|website=Guns.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-02}}</ref> Lawsuits (''National Rifle Association v. City of Philadelphia'') are pending.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pennlive.com/midstate/2015/09/philadelphia_act_192_gun_lawsu.html|title=Philly judge rules NRA has no 'legal standing' to sue city over gun ordinances|last=Vendel|first=Christine|date=2015-09-04|website=pennlive.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-13}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, the [[Erie, Pennsylvania|City of Erie]] had its local ordinance prohibiting firearms in city parks invalidated in ''Dillon v. City of Erie''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://caselaw.findlaw.com/pa-commonwealth-court/1654285.html|title=FindLaw's Commonwealth Court of Pennsylvania case and opinions.|website=Findlaw|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.princelaw.com/2014/01/07/press-release-attorney-joshua-prince-secures-major-victory-against-city-of-erie/|title=PRESS RELEASE: Attorney Joshua Prince Secures Major Victory Against City of Erie|last=Prince|first=Joshua|last2=Esq.|date=2014-01-07|website=Prince Law Offices Blog|language=en|access-date=2019-09-13}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, the [[Harrisburg, Pennsylvania|City of Harrisburg]] enacted ordinances prohibiting firearm possession by minors, discharging firearms within the city, mandatory reporting of lost or stolen firearms within 48 hours, and firearm sale, display and long gun possession in public restrictions during a state of emergency; legal challenges are pending.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pennlive.com/midstate/2015/01/harrisburg_sued_gun_ordinances.html|title='Major financial hit' looming for Harrisburg, says legal defense group suing over firearm ordinances|last=Vendel|first=Christine|date=2015-01-14|website=pennlive.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-13}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://blog.princelaw.com/2019/09/12/monumental-decision-commonwealth-court-overrules-prior-decision-regarding-standing-to-bring-a-challenge-to-an-unlawful-firearm-ordinance/|title=MONUMENTAL DECISION \u2013 Commonwealth Court OVERRULES Prior Decision Regarding Standing to Bring a Challenge to an Unlawful Firearm Ordinance|date=2019-09-12|work=Prince Law Offices Blog|access-date=2019-09-13|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, the state legislature passed Act 192 which allowed gun owners and firearm advocacy groups to file suit against local municipalities for their gun control ordinances. In 2015, the Pennsylvania Supreme Court ruled in favor of Philadelphia, Lancaster, Pittsburgh and five democratic legislators that the act was unconstitutional on the grounds that bills must pertain to one subject. Act 192 was originally intended to criminalize the theft of metals and a provision was amended to add the part regarding [[Standing (law)|legal standing]] to challenge local firearm ordinances.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/pennsylvania-court-law-nra-gun-challenges/|title=Court tosses Pennsylvania law aiding NRA gun challenges|access-date=2018-03-16|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politicspa.com/commonwealth-court-strikes-down-act-192/67263/|title=Commonwealth Court Strikes Down Act 192|access-date=2019-09-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.legis.state.pa.us/cfdocs/billInfo/billInfo.cfm?sYear=2013&sInd=0&body=H&type=B&bn=0080|title=Bill Information - House Bill 80; Regular Session 2013-2014|website=The official website for the Pennsylvania General Assembly.|language=English|access-date=2019-09-13}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, [[Lower Merion Township, Pennsylvania|Lower Merion Township]] had its 2011 ordinance prohibiting carry or discharge of firearms in a park without a special permit invalidated in ''Firearm Owners Against Crime v. Lower Merion Township''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://blog.princelaw.com/2016/12/16/commonwealth-court-finds-lower-merion-townships-firearm-regulations-unlawful/|title=Commonwealth Court Finds Lower Merion Township's Firearm Regulations UNLAWFUL|date=2016-12-16|work=Prince Law Offices Blog|access-date=2019-09-13|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Pittsburgh attempted to ban firearms in city parks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://triblive.com/local/allegheny/12773533-74/pittsburgh-councilman-moves-to-ban-guns-in-city-parks-despite-opposition|title=Pittsburgh councilman moves to ban guns in city parks despite opposition|last=Bauder|first=Bob|website=TribLIVE.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-04-04}}</ref> On April 9, 2019, Pittsburgh enacted three gun control laws, prohibiting use of [[Assault weapon|assault weapons]], [[High-capacity magazine ban|magazines with capacities greater than 10]], and enacting a [[red flag law]]. These laws are being challenged as a violation of preemption.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/04/09/711401894/pittsburgh-restricts-use-of-assault-style-weapons-setting-up-court-fight|title=Pittsburgh Restricts Use Of Assault-Style Weapons, Setting Up Court Fight|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2019-04-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.princelaw.com/2019/04/09/pittsburgh-sued-over-illegal-anti-gun-enactments/|title=Pittsburgh Sued Over Illegal, Anti-Gun Enactments|last=Prince|first=Joshua|last2=Esq.|date=2019-04-09|website=Prince Law Offices Blog|language=en|access-date=2019-06-02}}</ref> Pittsburgh has agreed not to enforce the laws while the lawsuits proceed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pittsburgh.cbslocal.com/2019/05/20/pittsburgh-gun-control-legislation-stay-lawsuits/|title=City Of Pittsburgh Agrees Not To Enforce Gun Control Legislation During Ongoing Court Proceedings|date=2019-05-20|language=en|access-date=2019-06-03}}</ref> On October 29, 2019, the [[Court of common pleas (Pennsylvania)|Allegheny Court of Common Pleas]] invalidated all three ordinances as a violation of state preemption.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/religion/judge-tosses-pittsburgh-gun-laws-passed-after-massacre/2019/10/29/c85894c0-fa99-11e9-9e02-1d45cb3dfa8f_story.html|title=Judge tosses Pittsburgh gun laws passed after massacre|last=AP|first=Michael Rubinkam {{!}}|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=2019-11-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://princelaw.files.wordpress.com/2019/10/court-decision.pdf|title=Pittsburg lawsuit|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://htv-prod-media.s3.amazonaws.com/files/gun-ruling-1572383739.pdf|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> On November 18, 2019, Pittsburgh filed an appeal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.princelaw.com/2019/11/21/pittsburgh-appeals-ruling-that-its-ordinances-are-unlawful/|title=Pittsburgh Appeals Ruling That Its Ordinances Are Unlawful|last=Prince|first=Joshua|last2=Esq.|date=2019-11-21|website=Prince Law Offices Blog|language=en|access-date=2019-11-24}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, Philadelphia had an ordinance that requires the reporting of lost or stolen firearms enjoined.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.princelaw.com/2020/01/11/city-of-philadelphia-enjoined-from-enforcing-lost-and-stolen-firearm-ordinance/|title=City of Philadelphia ENJOINED from enforcing lost and stolen firearm ordinance|last=Prince|first=Joshua|last2=Esq.|date=2020-01-11|website=Prince Law Offices Blog|language=en|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\n=== Sanctuaries ===\nSome counties have adopted [[Second Amendment sanctuary]] resolutions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.morning-times.com/news/article_67f64c57-e267-566e-98da-07f8a574fa52.html|title=Bradford County declared 'Second Amendment Sanctuary County'|last=Writer|first=JOHNNY WILLIAMS Staff|website=morning-times.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref>\n\n== Purchasing a firearm ==\nPennsylvania state law refers to a handgun as a \"firearm\", while \"long gun\" is used to describe a shotgun, or rifle of a certain length or longer. Minimum age for purchasing a long gun is 18, and the age restriction for purchasing a handgun is 21. However, someone can own a handgun if he or she is 18 and received the handgun as a gift. \n\nTo purchase a firearm, buyers must be at least 18 years of age. They can never have been convicted of a violent crime, must not be an undocumented immigrant, declared mentally ill by the court, a drug addict or habitual drunkard, a fugitive from justice, have been convicted of three separate DUI charges within a five-year period (or just one charge if it is classified as a first degree misdemeanor which carries a sentence of up to 5 years)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pennlive.com/news/2017/07/dui_conviction_blocks_man_from.html|title=DUI conviction blocks man from owning a gun, Pa. court rules|last=Miller|first=Matt|date=2017-07-24|website=pennlive.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-18}}</ref> or are subject to an active protection from abuse order.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.pennlive.com/news/2016/01/how_to_buy_a_gun_in_pennsylvan.html|title=How to buy a gun in Pennsylvania|work=PennLive.com|access-date=2017-12-06|language=en-US}}</ref> State level charges which are punishable by a sentence of more than one year (even if no jail time is actually served) disqualifies one from purchasing firearms under federal law. However, several court rulings have declared such prohibitions unconstitutional; e.g. first degree misdemeanor DUI charge<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.princelaw.com/2018/10/01/monumental-decision-federal-court-rules-its-unconstitutional-to-strip-second-amendment-rights-as-a-result-of-a-second-dui/|title=MONUMENTAL DECISION \u2013 Federal Court Rules It's Unconstitutional to Strip Second Amendment Rights as a Result of a Second DUI|last=Prince|first=Joshua|last2=Esq.|date=2018-10-01|website=Prince Law Offices Blog|language=en|access-date=2019-07-18}}</ref> and furnishing counterfeit documents.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.princelaw.com/2019/02/04/federal-court-rules-firearms-prohibition-against-an-individual-for-a-misdemeanor-conviction-under-vehicle-code-is-unconstitutional/|title=Federal Court Rules Firearms Prohibition Against an Individual for a Misdemeanor Conviction Under Vehicle Code is Unconstitutional|last=Kraut|first=Adam|last2=Esq.|date=2019-02-04|website=Prince Law Offices Blog|language=en|access-date=2019-07-18}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the Pennsylvania Supreme Court held that for the Pennsylvania State Police (\u201cPSP\u201d) to deny an individual pursuant to an alleged federal firearms disability, the PSP must prove, in addition to the person being prohibited under 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 922(g), that the firearm moved in interstate commerce.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.princelaw.com/2019/07/18/pa-supreme-court-psp-must-prove-firearm-moved-in-interstate-commerce-to-deny-individual-under-federal-law/|title=PA Supreme Court \u2013 PSP Must Prove Firearm Moved in Interstate Commerce to Deny Individual under Federal Law|last=Prince|first=Joshua|last2=Esq.|date=2019-07-18|website=Prince Law Offices Blog|language=en|access-date=2019-07-18}}</ref>\n\nNo firearms are known to be prohibited by state law. Private sales of handguns must go through a licensed dealer, though long guns may be sold privately without the use of a licensed dealer. Licensed dealers must provide locking devices with handguns unless the handgun has a locking device incorporated in its design.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\nIn Pennsylvania, there are more than 2,500 federally licensed firearm dealers where one may make a purchase. Individuals interested in purchasing a firearm must first fill out an application with their basic information. Once the application has been completed, the firearms dealer will input the information into the&nbsp;Pennsylvania Instant Check System to check if the individual is legally allowed to own a firearm. On average in Pennsylvania, this background check costs $20.00 for handgun purchases and $25.00 for a long gun purchase.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\nResidents in Pennsylvania may also purchase firearms from gun shows and private individuals. When purchasing from a federally licensed dealer at a gun show, the process remains the same. When purchasing a long gun in a private sale, the buyer is exempt from obtaining a background check. When purchasing a handgun in a private sale, the buyer is legally required to complete a firearm transfer at a federally licensed dealer.&nbsp;There is a $2 fee for the instant check and a $3 firearm sale surcharge to cover telephone costs.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nraila.org/gun-laws/state-gun-laws/pennsylvania/|title=NRA-ILA {{!}} Pennsylvania Gun Laws|last=NRA-ILA|website=NRA-ILA|language=en|access-date=2017-12-06}}</ref>\n\nTransfers of handguns between spouses, parent and child, grandparent and grandchild or between active law enforcement officers are exempt from the above requirements. Rifles and shotguns may be transferred between unlicensed individuals. &nbsp;Antique firearms are exempt from the requirements regarding transfer of firearms through dealers.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Definition of a firearm ===\nThe Pennsylvania Uniform Firearms Act defines \"firearm\" as \"any pistol or revolver with a barrel less than 15 inches, any shotgun with a barrel less than 18 inches, any rifle with a barrel of less than 16 inches or any pistol, revolver, rifle or shotgun with an overall length of less than 26 inches.\"&nbsp; However, several sections of the law include a broader definition that includes all firearms, i.e. handguns, rifles and shotguns, and pertains to that section only.&nbsp; The distinction should be closely noted when interpreting the statutes.<ref name=\":1\" /> [[Pennsylvania Attorney General|Attorney General]] [[Josh Shapiro]] issued a legal opinion in December 2019 that 80% lower receivers are considered firearms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.attorneygeneral.gov/taking-action/press-releases/ag-shapiro-gov-wolf-80-receivers-are-firearms/|title=AG Shapiro, Gov. Wolf: 80% Receivers Are Firearms|website=Pennsylvania Office of Attorney General|language=en|access-date=2020-01-11}}</ref> A legal challenge ensued<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firearmspolicy.org/evanchick|title=PAFirearmCase.com - Landmark Firearms, et al. v. PSP Commissioner Robert Evanchick|website=Firearms Policy Coalition|language=en|access-date=2020-01-11}}</ref> and the [[Commonwealth Court of Pennsylvania|Commonwealth Court]] issued a [[preliminary injunction]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.princelaw.com/2020/01/31/injunction-granted-against-pennsylvania-state-polices-policy-relating-to-partially-manufactured-frames-and-receivers/|title=Injunction GRANTED against Pennsylvania State Police\u2019s Policy relating to \u201cPartially-Manufactured Frames and Receivers\u201d|last=Prince|first=Joshua|last2=Esq.|date=2020-01-31|website=Prince Law Offices Blog|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yorkdispatch.com/story/news/local/pennsylvania/2020/02/02/pennsylvania-judge-puts-hold-state-ghost-guns-policy/41128331/|title=Pennsylvania judge puts hold on state \u2018ghost guns\u2019 policy|website=York Dispatch|language=en|access-date=2020-02-05}}</ref>\n\n=== Gun dealer requirements ===\nDealers are prohibited from transferring the firearm if the Pennsylvania State Police has issued a \"temporary delay\" in order to investigate whether the person has been convicted of a domestic violence misdemeanor that disqualifies the person from firearm possession.\n\nTo sell a handgun or short-barreled rifle or shotgun, a dealer must also:<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://lawcenter.giffords.org/background-checks-in-pennsylvania/|title=Background Checks in Pennsylvania {{!}} Giffords Law Center to Prevent Gun Violence|date=2017-11-27|work=Giffords Law Center to Prevent Gun Violence|access-date=2017-12-06|language=en-US}}</ref>&nbsp;\n* Require the purchaser to complete a purchase application, which includes a statement that the purchaser is the actual buyer of the firearm. The dealer must retain a copy of the application for at least 20 years, mail the original to Pennsylvania State Police within 14 days of the sale, and provide one copy to the purchaser;&nbsp;\n* Record the approval number on the application; and&nbsp;\n* If the purchaser passes the background check, deliver the firearm to the purchaser securely wrapped and unloaded.<ref>18 Pa. Cons. Stat. Ann. \u00a7 6111(a), (b); 37 Pa. Code \u00a7 33.111. For more information about the procedures that licensed dealers must follow to complete the sale, please see the administrative regulations of PSP available at 37 Pa. Code \u00a7\u00a7 33.102-33.113.</ref>\n\n== Concealed carry and transport ==\nIndividuals in Pennsylvania are permitted to open carry firearms as long as the firearm is in plain view. When concealing a firearm, individuals must obtain a License To Carry Firearms from the local sheriffs' office. An individual must have a License To Carry Firearms to carry a handgun in a vehicle in Pennsylvania, Long guns are not allowed to be transported loaded.&nbsp;&nbsp;\n\nIn the only first-class city, Philadelphia, a license is required for both concealed carry, and open carry. A total of 31 states recognized Pennsylvania's license to concealed carry.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.yorkdispatch.com/story/news/politics/2017/10/09/constitutional-carry-pennsylvania-challenged-gun-control-advocates/735599001/|title='Constitutional carry' in Pennsylvania challenged by gun control advocates|work=York Dispatch|access-date=2017-12-07|language=en}}</ref>\n\nWhen transporting firearms in Pennsylvania without a Concealed Carry Permit, the firearm and ammunition must be in two separate containers within the vehicle.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nTo apply for a license to carry in Pennsylvania, individuals must be at least 21 years of age. The application process requires submitting the&nbsp;Pennsylvania License to Carry Firearms application to the sheriff of the county in which they reside. Individuals who are not residents of Pennsylvania but are 21 years of age or older may submit the Application for a Pennsylvania License to Carry Firearms to any Pennsylvania County Sheriff's office along with the required fee.&nbsp;<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.psp.pa.gov/firearms-information/Pages/Carrying-Firearms-in-Pennsylvania.aspx|title=Carrying Firearms in Pennsylvania|website=www.psp.pa.gov|language=en-us|access-date=2017-12-06}}</ref>\n\nFirearms are prohibited from certain places, including federal court facilities; all other court facilities must provide a locker to secure firearms while conducting business within the court facility as per 18 Pa.C.S 913 (e). Concealed carry on school property used to be an unsettled area of the law with many in law enforcement arguing that the practice is absolutely prohibited and firearms right supporters arguing that 18 Pa.C.S. 912(c) permits those who have a concealed carry license to carry on school grounds as an \"other lawful purpose.\" On February 16, 2017, the [[Superior Court of Pennsylvania|Superior Court]] ruled in the case of ''Commonwealth v. Goslin'' that the \"other lawful purpose\" clause is a valid defense for people who are otherwise carrying a weapon legally on school grounds regardless of any connection to a school activity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.princelaw.com/2017/02/16/the-goslin-decisions-impact-on-possessing-weapons-on-school-property/|title=The Goslin Decision's Impact on Possessing Weapons on School Property|last=Prince|first=Joshua|last2=Esq.|date=2017-02-16|website=Prince Law Offices, P.C.|access-date=2017-06-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.handgunlaw.us/documents/PASupremeCtCarryOnSchoolProperty.pdf|title=Commonwealth v. Goslin}}</ref> Carrying a handgun on public streets and public property of Philadelphia, or in a vehicle anywhere in the state, or concealed on or about one's person anywhere in the state is prohibited without a \"License To Carry Firearms\" (LTCF) or a license or permit issued by another state which is honored by Pennsylvania for that purpose.<ref name=LCAV-PA>[http://smartgunlaws.org/pennsylvania-state-law-summary/ \"Pennsylvania State Law Summary\"], Law Center to Prevent Gun Violence. Retrieved January 2, 2013.</ref><ref name=NRA-ILA-PA>[https://www.nraila.org/gun-laws/state-gun-laws/pennsylvania/ \"State Gun Laws: Pennsylvania\"], National Rifle Association \u2013 Institute for Legislative Action. Retrieved December 27, 2015.</ref> A LTCF is generally not required to openly carry a firearm on or about one's person, except in a vehicle or in Philadelphia, or during a declared State of Emergency.<ref name=\"pafoa-open-carry\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pafoa.org/law/carrying-firearms/open-carry|title=Pennsylvania Firearm Owners Association \u2013 Open Carry|date=2007-10-02|publisher=Pafoa.org|accessdate=2012-05-22}}</ref> \nA bill proposed in September 2014 would allow teachers and school employees to carry guns.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyitem.com/news/state/article_7db6a8d4-d559-5526-8f6f-1760c7f9a2f3.html|title=Response mixed on bill to let teachers carry guns|last1=Gautz|first1=Chris|publisher=The Daily Item}}</ref>\n\nPennsylvania [[shall issue]] a LTCF to resident and non-resident applicants if no good cause exists to deny the license. Non-resident applicants must first obtain a license from their home state, unless their home state does not issue licenses.<ref name=\"LCAV-PA\" /><ref name=\"NRA-ILA-PA\" />\n\n== Laws and regulations ==\nArticle DIUS DUCK ania General Assembly. Retrieved January 17, 2018.</ref>\n\nPennsylvania has state preemption for regulation of the lawful ownership, possession, transfer or transportation of firearms, ammunition, or ammunition components. That is, only state laws, not local laws, can regulate those matters.<ref name=\"LCAV-PA\"/><ref name=\"NRA-ILA-PA\"/>\n\nMost items that are required to be registered under the National Firearms Act such as machine guns, suppressors, short barreled rifles and shotguns, are prohibited in Pennsylvania as \"offensive weapons\" unless they are registered under the NFA.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThere are no regulating laws for the sale, purchase, or possession of ammunition. Use of armor-piercing ammunition for criminal activities is specifically prohibited by statute.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.legis.state.pa.us/cfdocs/legis/LI/consCheck.cfm?txtType=HTM&ttl=18&div=0&chpt=61&sctn=21&subsctn=0&mobile_choice=suppress|title=Title 18|last=Center|first=Legislativate Data Processing|website=The official website for the Pennsylvania General Assembly.|language=en|access-date=2018-11-24}}</ref> \n\nPennsylvania law requires that information received by the [[Pennsylvania State Police]] pursuant to a sale is destroyed within 72 hours of the completion of the background check.<ref name=\"LCAV-PA\" /><ref name=\"NRA-ILA-PA\" /> The [http://www.pafoa.org Pennsylvania Firearm Owners Association] notes that the [[Pennsylvania State Police]] nonetheless keep a \"sales database\" of all handguns purchased within the state.<ref name=\"pafoa-pa-sales-database\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pafoa.org/law#faq-do-i-have-to-register-my-guns|title=Pennsylvania Firearm/Gun Law|date=2007-10-02|publisher=Pafoa.org|accessdate=2012-07-09}}</ref> The database was challenged based on what was asserted as the unambiguous text of the statute, specifically \"nothing... ...shall be construed to allow any government or law enforcement agency or any agent thereof to create, maintain or operate any registry of firearm ownership within this Commonwealth\" (full statute text above), the Pennsylvania Supreme Court nonetheless ruled in ''Allegheny County Sportsmen's League v. Rendell'', 860 A.2d 10\n(Pa. 2004), that Pennsylvania's database of handgun sales is not prohibited by state law because the registration was only of handgun sales and not of all guns.<ref name=\"LCAV-REGISTRATION\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lcav.org/content/registration_firearms.pdf|title=LCAV. Registration of Firearms. In Regulating Guns in America: An Evaluation and Comparative Analysis of Federal, State, and Selected Local Gun Laws (2008). Retrieved July 8, 2011.|date=|accessdate=2012-05-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120406205718/http://www.lcav.org/content/registration_firearms.pdf|archive-date=April 6, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Law of Pennsylvania]]\n* [[Uniform Firearms Act]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Gun laws in the United States (by state)}}\n\n[[Category:Pennsylvania law]]\n[[Category:United States gun laws by state|Pennsylvania]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Map of USA PA.svg |thumb|Location of Pennsylvania in the United States]]\n'''Gun laws in Pennsylvania''' regulate the sale, possession, and use of [[firearm]]s and [[ammunition]] in the [[Commonwealth (U.S. state)|Commonwealth]] of [[Pennsylvania]] in the United States.<ref name=LCAV-PA>[http://smartgunlaws.org/pennsylvania-state-law-summary/ \"Pennsylvania State Law Summary\"], Law Center to Prevent Gun Violence. Retrieved January 2, 2013.</ref><ref name=NRA-ILA-PA>[https://www.nraila.org/gun-laws/state-gun-laws/pennsylvania/ \"State Gun Laws: Pennsylvania\"], National Rifle Association \u2013 Institute for Legislative Action. Retrieved December 27, 2015.</ref><ref name=batfe-book-2007>{{cite web |url=http://www.atf.gov/publications/download/p/atf-p-5300-5.pdf |title=Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms, and Explosives \u2013 State Laws and Published Ordinances \u2013 Firearms |accessdate=January 2, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111109215323/http://www.atf.gov/publications/download/p/atf-p-5300-5.pdf |archive-date=November 9, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Summary table==\n<!-- Transcludes to [[Gun laws in the United States (by state)]] --><onlyinclude>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"font-size:85%; width:95%;\"\n|-\n! Subject/Law !! Long guns!! Handguns !! Relevant statutes !! Notes\n|-\n| State permit required to purchase? || No || No ||||\n|-\n| Firearm registration? || No || Partial || [http://www.legis.state.pa.us/cfdocs/legis/LI/consCheck.cfm?txtType=HTM&ttl=18&div=0&chpt=61 18 Pa.C.S. \u00a7 6111.4] || 18 Pa.C.S. \u00a7 6111.4 forbids the government from creating a firearm registry. Nevertheless, all handgun buyers in the state must undergo a PICS check at the point of sale, a record of which is maintained by the state police in a \"sales database\". The [[Pennsylvania Supreme Court]] has ruled that this is legal under the aforementioned statue, as it is not a comprehensive record of all handgun ownership within the state \u2014 gun owners moving into the state are not required to register their firearms.\n|-\n| Assault weapon law? || No || No || ||\n|-\n| Owner license required? || No || No || || \n|-\n| License required for concealed carry? || N/A || Yes || [http://www.legis.state.pa.us/WU01/LI/LI/CT/HTM/18/00.061..HTM 18 Pa.C.S. \u00a7 6109] || License to Carry Firearms issued on a \"shall-issue\" basis. A LTCF is required to carry a firearm concealed on one's person, in a vehicle, or during a declared state of emergency.\n|-\n| License required for open carry? || No || No || || Unlicensed open-carry, except license required in Philadelphia (City of the First Class) and when within a vehicle.\nOn May 31, 2019, the [[Supreme Court of Pennsylvania|Pennsylvania Supreme Court]] ruled that carrying a firearm is not reasonable suspicion to detain someone.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.princelaw.com/2019/05/31/monumental-decision-from-the-pennsylvania-supreme-court-regarding-whether-the-open-carrying-of-a-firearm-is-reasonable-suspicion-of-a-crime/|title=MONUMENTAL Decision from the Pennsylvania Supreme Court regarding whether the Open Carrying of a Firearm is Reasonable Suspicion of a Crime|last=Prince|first=Joshua|last2=Esq.|date=2019-05-31|website=Prince Law Offices Blog|language=en|access-date=2019-05-31}}</ref>\n|-\n| Castle Law/Stand Your Ground? || Yes || Yes || [http://www.legis.state.pa.us/CFDOCS/Legis/PN/Public/btCheck.cfm?txtType=HTM&sessYr=2011&sessInd=0&billBody=H&billTyp=B&billNbr=0040] || Castle Law. No duty to retreat inside castle. No duty to retreat outside castle if confronted with a deadly weapon or an object that appears to be one in a place where the person has a right to be.\n|-\n| State preemption of local restrictions? || Yes || Yes || [http://www.legis.state.pa.us/WU01/LI/LI/CT/HTM/18/00.061..HTM 18 Pa.C.S. \u00a7 6120] ||\n|-\n| [[National Firearms Act|NFA]] weapons restricted? || No || No || ||\n|-\n| Peaceable Journey laws? || Yes || Yes || [http://www.psp.pa.gov/firearms-information/Pages/Carrying-Firearms-in-Pennsylvania.aspx#.VOuuQy7e8rc] || Non-residents may carry in a vehicle if in possession of a valid carry permit from any state. Otherwise, federal rules observed.\n|-\n| Background checks required for private sales? || No || Yes || || All private party transfers of handguns must be processed through a licensed dealer, or at a county sheriff's office. In either case a background check is required.\n|}</onlyinclude>\n\n== State gun legislation==\n\n=== Act 192 of 2014 ===\nAct 192 of 2014 allowed gun owners and firearm advocacy groups to file suit against local municipalities for their gun control ordinances.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/pennsylvania-court-law-nra-gun-challenges/|title=Court tosses Pennsylvania law aiding NRA gun challenges|access-date=2018-04-25|language=en}}</ref> Philadelphia, Lancaster, Pittsburgh and five democratic legislators filed suit on the grounds that the act was unconstitutional.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.phillymag.com/news/2016/06/21/pa-supreme-court-rules-nra-backed-law-unconstitutional/|title=Pa Supreme Court Rules NRA-backed Law Unconstitutional|date=2016-06-21|work=Philadelphia Magazine|access-date=2018-04-25|language=en-US}}</ref> The Pennsylvania Supreme Court ruled in favor of the cities and five legislator that the act was unconstitutional on the grounds that bills must pertain to one subject. Act 192 of 2014 was originally intended to criminalize the theft of metals.The firearm part of the act was a provision. City Solicitor Sozi Tulante released a statement against the bill: \"Act 192 was passed by the General Assembly without any public notice or debate, and would have flooded the courts with advocacy litigation even when the plaintiffs had no real legal stake in the case.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.phillymag.com/news/2016/06/21/pa-supreme-court-rules-nra-backed-law-unconstitutional/|title=Pa Supreme Court Rules NRA-backed Law Unconstitutional|date=2016-06-21|work=Philadelphia Magazine|access-date=2018-04-04|language=en-US}}</ref> Senator Daylin Leach, one of the five democrats to file suite stated: \"municipalities that repealed ordinances may now restore them\" During the case they found the law unconstitutional Justice David N. Wecht said \"If, by brute force, the majority of the General Assembly can cram through any number of regulations.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.philly.com/philly/news/politics/20160310_Pa__justices_question_roots_of_NRA-friendly_law.html|title=Pa. justices question roots of NRA-backed law - Philly|work=Philly.com|access-date=2018-04-04}}</ref>\n\n=== House Bill 170 of 2017 ===\nHouse Bill 170, introduced by Rick Saccone removed the requirement of obtaining a license in the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania to be able to legally conceal a firearm.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.yorkdispatch.com/story/news/politics/2017/10/09/constitutional-carry-pennsylvania-challenged-gun-control-advocates/735599001/|title='Constitutional carry' in Pennsylvania challenged by gun control advocates|work=York Dispatch|access-date=2018-04-25|language=en}}</ref> The Commonwealth has no requirement to be licensed to carry a firearm openly. Saccone stated \"If a citizen passes a criminal background check to purchase a new firearm, it is patently unjust and unconstitutionally questionable to add layers of bureaucratic regulations on those who are least likely to commit a crime just because the citizen prefers to carry his weapon concealed.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.yorkdispatch.com/story/news/politics/2017/10/09/constitutional-carry-pennsylvania-challenged-gun-control-advocates/735599001/|title='Constitutional carry' in Pennsylvania challenged by gun control advocates|work=York Dispatch|access-date=2018-03-27|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Senate Bill 383 of 2017 ===\nSenate Bill 383 gives school boards the authority to establish policies and protocols to allow staff members to carry concealed firearms on school property.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://fox43.com/2017/06/28/pa-senate-passes-bill-clearing-way-for-schools-to-allow-employees-guns-on-campus-with/|title=Pa. Senate passes bill clearing way for schools to allow employees' guns on campus|date=2017-06-28|work=WPMT FOX43|access-date=2018-04-25|language=en-US}}</ref> There is no mandated school participation. Staff members choosing to carry concealed firearms must do so legally.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://fox43.com/2017/06/28/pa-senate-passes-bill-clearing-way-for-schools-to-allow-employees-guns-on-campus-with/|title=Pa. Senate passes bill clearing way for schools to allow employees' guns on campus|date=2017-06-28|work=WPMT FOX43|access-date=2018-04-25|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== House Bill 921 of 2014 ===\nAuthored by rep. Timothy Krieger, the intent of the bill was to eliminate the Pennsylvania Instant Check System in favor of the National Instant Check System and allowing the Federal government to administer the background check instead of state police.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pennlive.com/midstate/index.ssf/2014/03/gun_background_check_bill_penn.html|title=Bill to eliminate Pa. background checks for gun buyers on hold until questions about national system resolved|work=PennLive.com|access-date=2018-04-25|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== House Bill 501 of 2017 ===\nLegislation to remove the second amendment rights of known domestic abusers while removing the ability to surrender their weapons to a third party and replacing the 60 days waiting period with a 24 hour order to surrender their firearms. Senator Thomas Killon's sponsorship memo stated \"The intent of this change in law is to enhance safety for parties and their children in domestic violations and protection from abuse situations. Enhancing their safety during these difficult times helps not only these families but also law enforcement charged with overall public safety.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.legis.state.pa.us/cfdocs/Legis/CSM/showMemoPublic.cfm?chamber=S&SPick=20170&cosponId=21693|title=Senate Co-Sponsorship Memoranda|last=Center|first=Legislativate Data Processing|website=The official website for the Pennsylvania General Assembly.|language=en|access-date=2018-04-04}}</ref> Governor Tom Wolf also supported the bill, stating on its behalf \" we must protect victims, spouses, and children of domestic violence and attempt to prevent domestic abusers from escalating their violence in everyday places that result in mass murder.\" \"It is time for the General Assembly to act on this bipartisan, commonsense legislation to protect victims and reduce violence.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.governor.pa.gov/wolf-calls-passage-bipartisan-enhanced-firearm-prohibition-domestic-abusers/|title=Gov. Wolf Calls for Enhanced Firearm Prohibition for Domestic Abusers|date=2017-11-13|work=Governor Tom Wolf|access-date=2018-04-04|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Local legislation and preemption==\n\n=== ''Ortiz v. Commonwealth'' ===\nIn 1993, two [[Home Rule Municipality (Pennsylvania)|Home Rule Municipalities]], [[Philadelphia]] and [[Pittsburgh]], attempted to regulate [[Assault weapon|assault weapons]]. On June 17, 1993, the [[mayor of Philadelphia]] [[Ed Rendell]] signed and approved Bill No. 508 submitted by the [[Philadelphia City Council]], which banned certain types of [[Assault weapon|assault weapons]] in [[Philadelphia County]]. In 1994, the [[Pittsburgh City Council]] passed Ordinance 30-1994, which also banned certain specified assault weapons within Pittsburgh's physical boundaries. These ordinances planned to regulate the ownership, use, possession or transfer of certain firearms. After these ordinances were enacted the [[Pennsylvania General Assembly|General Assembly]] passed House Bill 185 on October 4, 1994, which amended Title 18 of the Crimes Code, including the Pennsylvania [[Uniform Firearms Act]], 18 Pa.C.S. \u00a7\u00a7 6101-6124. The amendment, which appears at 18 Pa.C.S. \u00a7 6120, provided that no county, municipality or township could regulate the ownership or transfer of firearms or ammunition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.legis.state.pa.us/WU01/LI/LI/CT/HTM/18/00.061.020.000..HTM|title=Section 6120 - Title 18 - CRIMES AND OFFENSES|website=www.legis.state.pa.us|access-date=2019-06-02}}</ref>\n\nCouncilman Angel Ortiz of [[Philadelphia City Council]] and other Philadelphia appellants brought an action against the state in the [[Commonwealth Court of Pennsylvania]], arguing that the state had exceeded its jurisdiction over the Home Rule Municipalities in this case. The Philadelphia appellants argued that only in Philadelphia must a person obtain a license for carrying any firearm, on a public street or public property, regardless of whether it is unconcealed or concealed. Throughout the rest of Pennsylvania, a license is only necessary if one is carrying a [[Concealed carry in the United States|concealed firearm]] or is carrying one in a vehicle. 18 Pa.C.S.A. 6106(a).\n\nIn 1996, the [[Supreme Court of Pennsylvania|Pennsylvania Supreme Court]] ruled that the state preemption statute was valid and that Philadelphia and Pittsburgh could not enact stricter gun control laws.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lawcenter.giffords.org/local-authority-to-regulate-firearms-in-pennsylvania/|title=Local Authority to Regulate Firearms in Pennsylvania|date=2018-10-23|website=Giffords Law Center to Prevent Gun Violence|language=en|access-date=2019-06-02}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2008/03/06/controlling-guns-in-philadelphia|title=Controlling Guns in Philadelphia}}</ref>\n\n=== Further attempts ===\nIn 2008, [[Philadelphia]] had seven different 2007 ordinances invalidated in ''Clarke v. House of Representatives''; they included a limit of 1 handgun purchase per month and prohibiting straw purchases, reporting lost or stolen firearms, license requirement to acquire firearm or to bring one into the city, annual gun license renewal, firearm confiscation from someone posing a risk of harm, banning possession or transfer of assault rifles, and reporting requirements for ammunition sales.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://blog.princelaw.com/2015/01/16/press-release-lawsuit-filed-against-city-of-harrisburg-regarding-its-illegal-firearm-and-ammunition-ordinances/|title=PRESS RELEASE: Lawsuit Filed Against City of Harrisburg Regarding Its Illegal Firearm and Ammunition Ordinances|last=Offices|first=Prince Law|last2=P.C.|date=2015-01-16|website=Prince Law Offices Blog|language=en|access-date=2019-09-13}}</ref> In April 2008, the city sought to reenact the ordinances with minor changes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/sites/default/files/federalistsociety_pennsylvaniawhitepaperfinal_0.pdf|title=Key Issues for Pennsylvanians: What Is at Stake with the Pennsylvania Supreme Court|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The [[Philadelphia City Council]] proposed in 2016 to mandate all firearm owners with minors living in their custody lock their firearms at all times. The firearms must also be in a locked area with ammunition also being in a locked area; separate from the firearm.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gambonelaw.com/blog/can-philly-pass-its-own-gun-control-law-.cfm|title=The Problem with Philadelphia's Gun Control Proposal|work=Gambone Law|access-date=2018-04-04|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.guns.com/news/2016/06/06/philadelphia-moves-to-mandate-gun-lock-use|title=Philadelphia moves to mandate gun lock use|date=2016-06-06|website=Guns.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-02}}</ref> Lawsuits (''National Rifle Association v. City of Philadelphia'') are pending.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pennlive.com/midstate/2015/09/philadelphia_act_192_gun_lawsu.html|title=Philly judge rules NRA has no 'legal standing' to sue city over gun ordinances|last=Vendel|first=Christine|date=2015-09-04|website=pennlive.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-13}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, the [[Erie, Pennsylvania|City of Erie]] had its local ordinance prohibiting firearms in city parks invalidated in ''Dillon v. City of Erie''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://caselaw.findlaw.com/pa-commonwealth-court/1654285.html|title=FindLaw's Commonwealth Court of Pennsylvania case and opinions.|website=Findlaw|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.princelaw.com/2014/01/07/press-release-attorney-joshua-prince-secures-major-victory-against-city-of-erie/|title=PRESS RELEASE: Attorney Joshua Prince Secures Major Victory Against City of Erie|last=Prince|first=Joshua|last2=Esq.|date=2014-01-07|website=Prince Law Offices Blog|language=en|access-date=2019-09-13}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, the [[Harrisburg, Pennsylvania|City of Harrisburg]] enacted ordinances prohibiting firearm possession by minors, discharging firearms within the city, mandatory reporting of lost or stolen firearms within 48 hours, and firearm sale, display and long gun possession in public restrictions during a state of emergency; legal challenges are pending.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pennlive.com/midstate/2015/01/harrisburg_sued_gun_ordinances.html|title='Major financial hit' looming for Harrisburg, says legal defense group suing over firearm ordinances|last=Vendel|first=Christine|date=2015-01-14|website=pennlive.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-13}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://blog.princelaw.com/2019/09/12/monumental-decision-commonwealth-court-overrules-prior-decision-regarding-standing-to-bring-a-challenge-to-an-unlawful-firearm-ordinance/|title=MONUMENTAL DECISION \u2013 Commonwealth Court OVERRULES Prior Decision Regarding Standing to Bring a Challenge to an Unlawful Firearm Ordinance|date=2019-09-12|work=Prince Law Offices Blog|access-date=2019-09-13|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, the state legislature passed Act 192 which allowed gun owners and firearm advocacy groups to file suit against local municipalities for their gun control ordinances. In 2015, the Pennsylvania Supreme Court ruled in favor of Philadelphia, Lancaster, Pittsburgh and five democratic legislators that the act was unconstitutional on the grounds that bills must pertain to one subject. Act 192 was originally intended to criminalize the theft of metals and a provision was amended to add the part regarding [[Standing (law)|legal standing]] to challenge local firearm ordinances.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/pennsylvania-court-law-nra-gun-challenges/|title=Court tosses Pennsylvania law aiding NRA gun challenges|access-date=2018-03-16|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politicspa.com/commonwealth-court-strikes-down-act-192/67263/|title=Commonwealth Court Strikes Down Act 192|access-date=2019-09-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.legis.state.pa.us/cfdocs/billInfo/billInfo.cfm?sYear=2013&sInd=0&body=H&type=B&bn=0080|title=Bill Information - House Bill 80; Regular Session 2013-2014|website=The official website for the Pennsylvania General Assembly.|language=English|access-date=2019-09-13}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, [[Lower Merion Township, Pennsylvania|Lower Merion Township]] had its 2011 ordinance prohibiting carry or discharge of firearms in a park without a special permit invalidated in ''Firearm Owners Against Crime v. Lower Merion Township''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://blog.princelaw.com/2016/12/16/commonwealth-court-finds-lower-merion-townships-firearm-regulations-unlawful/|title=Commonwealth Court Finds Lower Merion Township's Firearm Regulations UNLAWFUL|date=2016-12-16|work=Prince Law Offices Blog|access-date=2019-09-13|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Pittsburgh attempted to ban firearms in city parks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://triblive.com/local/allegheny/12773533-74/pittsburgh-councilman-moves-to-ban-guns-in-city-parks-despite-opposition|title=Pittsburgh councilman moves to ban guns in city parks despite opposition|last=Bauder|first=Bob|website=TribLIVE.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-04-04}}</ref> On April 9, 2019, Pittsburgh enacted three gun control laws, prohibiting use of [[Assault weapon|assault weapons]], [[High-capacity magazine ban|magazines with capacities greater than 10]], and enacting a [[red flag law]]. These laws are being challenged as a violation of preemption.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/04/09/711401894/pittsburgh-restricts-use-of-assault-style-weapons-setting-up-court-fight|title=Pittsburgh Restricts Use Of Assault-Style Weapons, Setting Up Court Fight|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2019-04-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.princelaw.com/2019/04/09/pittsburgh-sued-over-illegal-anti-gun-enactments/|title=Pittsburgh Sued Over Illegal, Anti-Gun Enactments|last=Prince|first=Joshua|last2=Esq.|date=2019-04-09|website=Prince Law Offices Blog|language=en|access-date=2019-06-02}}</ref> Pittsburgh has agreed not to enforce the laws while the lawsuits proceed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pittsburgh.cbslocal.com/2019/05/20/pittsburgh-gun-control-legislation-stay-lawsuits/|title=City Of Pittsburgh Agrees Not To Enforce Gun Control Legislation During Ongoing Court Proceedings|date=2019-05-20|language=en|access-date=2019-06-03}}</ref> On October 29, 2019, the [[Court of common pleas (Pennsylvania)|Allegheny Court of Common Pleas]] invalidated all three ordinances as a violation of state preemption.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/religion/judge-tosses-pittsburgh-gun-laws-passed-after-massacre/2019/10/29/c85894c0-fa99-11e9-9e02-1d45cb3dfa8f_story.html|title=Judge tosses Pittsburgh gun laws passed after massacre|last=AP|first=Michael Rubinkam {{!}}|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=2019-11-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://princelaw.files.wordpress.com/2019/10/court-decision.pdf|title=Pittsburg lawsuit|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://htv-prod-media.s3.amazonaws.com/files/gun-ruling-1572383739.pdf|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> On November 18, 2019, Pittsburgh filed an appeal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.princelaw.com/2019/11/21/pittsburgh-appeals-ruling-that-its-ordinances-are-unlawful/|title=Pittsburgh Appeals Ruling That Its Ordinances Are Unlawful|last=Prince|first=Joshua|last2=Esq.|date=2019-11-21|website=Prince Law Offices Blog|language=en|access-date=2019-11-24}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, Philadelphia had an ordinance that requires the reporting of lost or stolen firearms enjoined.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.princelaw.com/2020/01/11/city-of-philadelphia-enjoined-from-enforcing-lost-and-stolen-firearm-ordinance/|title=City of Philadelphia ENJOINED from enforcing lost and stolen firearm ordinance|last=Prince|first=Joshua|last2=Esq.|date=2020-01-11|website=Prince Law Offices Blog|language=en|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\n=== Sanctuaries ===\nSome counties have adopted [[Second Amendment sanctuary]] resolutions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.morning-times.com/news/article_67f64c57-e267-566e-98da-07f8a574fa52.html|title=Bradford County declared 'Second Amendment Sanctuary County'|last=Writer|first=JOHNNY WILLIAMS Staff|website=morning-times.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref>\n\n== Purchasing a firearm ==\nPennsylvania state law refers to a handgun as a \"firearm\", while \"long gun\" is used to describe a shotgun, or rifle of a certain length or longer. Minimum age for purchasing a long gun is 18, and the age restriction for purchasing a handgun is 21. However, someone can own a handgun if he or she is 18 and received the handgun as a gift. \n\nTo purchase a firearm, buyers must be at least 18 years of age. They can never have been convicted of a violent crime, must not be an undocumented immigrant, declared mentally ill by the court, a drug addict or habitual drunkard, a fugitive from justice, have been convicted of three separate DUI charges within a five-year period (or just one charge if it is classified as a first degree misdemeanor which carries a sentence of up to 5 years)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pennlive.com/news/2017/07/dui_conviction_blocks_man_from.html|title=DUI conviction blocks man from owning a gun, Pa. court rules|last=Miller|first=Matt|date=2017-07-24|website=pennlive.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-18}}</ref> or are subject to an active protection from abuse order.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.pennlive.com/news/2016/01/how_to_buy_a_gun_in_pennsylvan.html|title=How to buy a gun in Pennsylvania|work=PennLive.com|access-date=2017-12-06|language=en-US}}</ref> State level charges which are punishable by a sentence of more than one year (even if no jail time is actually served) disqualifies one from purchasing firearms under federal law. However, several court rulings have declared such prohibitions unconstitutional; e.g. first degree misdemeanor DUI charge<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.princelaw.com/2018/10/01/monumental-decision-federal-court-rules-its-unconstitutional-to-strip-second-amendment-rights-as-a-result-of-a-second-dui/|title=MONUMENTAL DECISION \u2013 Federal Court Rules It's Unconstitutional to Strip Second Amendment Rights as a Result of a Second DUI|last=Prince|first=Joshua|last2=Esq.|date=2018-10-01|website=Prince Law Offices Blog|language=en|access-date=2019-07-18}}</ref> and furnishing counterfeit documents.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.princelaw.com/2019/02/04/federal-court-rules-firearms-prohibition-against-an-individual-for-a-misdemeanor-conviction-under-vehicle-code-is-unconstitutional/|title=Federal Court Rules Firearms Prohibition Against an Individual for a Misdemeanor Conviction Under Vehicle Code is Unconstitutional|last=Kraut|first=Adam|last2=Esq.|date=2019-02-04|website=Prince Law Offices Blog|language=en|access-date=2019-07-18}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the Pennsylvania Supreme Court held that for the Pennsylvania State Police (\u201cPSP\u201d) to deny an individual pursuant to an alleged federal firearms disability, the PSP must prove, in addition to the person being prohibited under 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 922(g), that the firearm moved in interstate commerce.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.princelaw.com/2019/07/18/pa-supreme-court-psp-must-prove-firearm-moved-in-interstate-commerce-to-deny-individual-under-federal-law/|title=PA Supreme Court \u2013 PSP Must Prove Firearm Moved in Interstate Commerce to Deny Individual under Federal Law|last=Prince|first=Joshua|last2=Esq.|date=2019-07-18|website=Prince Law Offices Blog|language=en|access-date=2019-07-18}}</ref>\n\nNo firearms are known to be prohibited by state law. Private sales of handguns must go through a licensed dealer, though long guns may be sold privately without the use of a licensed dealer. Licensed dealers must provide locking devices with handguns unless the handgun has a locking device incorporated in its design.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\nIn Pennsylvania, there are more than 2,500 federally licensed firearm dealers where one may make a purchase. Individuals interested in purchasing a firearm must first fill out an application with their basic information. Once the application has been completed, the firearms dealer will input the information into the&nbsp;Pennsylvania Instant Check System to check if the individual is legally allowed to own a firearm. On average in Pennsylvania, this background check costs $20.00 for handgun purchases and $25.00 for a long gun purchase.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\nResidents in Pennsylvania may also purchase firearms from gun shows and private individuals. When purchasing from a federally licensed dealer at a gun show, the process remains the same. When purchasing a long gun in a private sale, the buyer is exempt from obtaining a background check. When purchasing a handgun in a private sale, the buyer is legally required to complete a firearm transfer at a federally licensed dealer.&nbsp;There is a $2 fee for the instant check and a $3 firearm sale surcharge to cover telephone costs.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nraila.org/gun-laws/state-gun-laws/pennsylvania/|title=NRA-ILA {{!}} Pennsylvania Gun Laws|last=NRA-ILA|website=NRA-ILA|language=en|access-date=2017-12-06}}</ref>\n\nTransfers of handguns between spouses, parent and child, grandparent and grandchild or between active law enforcement officers are exempt from the above requirements. Rifles and shotguns may be transferred between unlicensed individuals. &nbsp;Antique firearms are exempt from the requirements regarding transfer of firearms through dealers.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Definition of a firearm ===\nThe Pennsylvania Uniform Firearms Act defines \"firearm\" as \"any pistol or revolver with a barrel less than 15 inches, any shotgun with a barrel less than 18 inches, any rifle with a barrel of less than 16 inches or any pistol, revolver, rifle or shotgun with an overall length of less than 26 inches.\"&nbsp; However, several sections of the law include a broader definition that includes all firearms, i.e. handguns, rifles and shotguns, and pertains to that section only.&nbsp; The distinction should be closely noted when interpreting the statutes.<ref name=\":1\" /> [[Pennsylvania Attorney General|Attorney General]] [[Josh Shapiro]] issued a legal opinion in December 2019 that 80% lower receivers are considered firearms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.attorneygeneral.gov/taking-action/press-releases/ag-shapiro-gov-wolf-80-receivers-are-firearms/|title=AG Shapiro, Gov. Wolf: 80% Receivers Are Firearms|website=Pennsylvania Office of Attorney General|language=en|access-date=2020-01-11}}</ref> A legal challenge ensued<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firearmspolicy.org/evanchick|title=PAFirearmCase.com - Landmark Firearms, et al. v. PSP Commissioner Robert Evanchick|website=Firearms Policy Coalition|language=en|access-date=2020-01-11}}</ref> and the [[Commonwealth Court of Pennsylvania|Commonwealth Court]] issued a [[preliminary injunction]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.princelaw.com/2020/01/31/injunction-granted-against-pennsylvania-state-polices-policy-relating-to-partially-manufactured-frames-and-receivers/|title=Injunction GRANTED against Pennsylvania State Police\u2019s Policy relating to \u201cPartially-Manufactured Frames and Receivers\u201d|last=Prince|first=Joshua|last2=Esq.|date=2020-01-31|website=Prince Law Offices Blog|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yorkdispatch.com/story/news/local/pennsylvania/2020/02/02/pennsylvania-judge-puts-hold-state-ghost-guns-policy/41128331/|title=Pennsylvania judge puts hold on state \u2018ghost guns\u2019 policy|website=York Dispatch|language=en|access-date=2020-02-05}}</ref>\n\n=== Gun dealer requirements ===\nDealers are prohibited from transferring the firearm if the Pennsylvania State Police has issued a \"temporary delay\" in order to investigate whether the person has been convicted of a domestic violence misdemeanor that disqualifies the person from firearm possession.\n\nTo sell a handgun or short-barreled rifle or shotgun, a dealer must also:<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://lawcenter.giffords.org/background-checks-in-pennsylvania/|title=Background Checks in Pennsylvania {{!}} Giffords Law Center to Prevent Gun Violence|date=2017-11-27|work=Giffords Law Center to Prevent Gun Violence|access-date=2017-12-06|language=en-US}}</ref>&nbsp;\n* Require the purchaser to complete a purchase application, which includes a statement that the purchaser is the actual buyer of the firearm. The dealer must retain a copy of the application for at least 20 years, mail the original to Pennsylvania State Police within 14 days of the sale, and provide one copy to the purchaser;&nbsp;\n* Record the approval number on the application; and&nbsp;\n* If the purchaser passes the background check, deliver the firearm to the purchaser securely wrapped and unloaded.<ref>18 Pa. Cons. Stat. Ann. \u00a7 6111(a), (b); 37 Pa. Code \u00a7 33.111. For more information about the procedures that licensed dealers must follow to complete the sale, please see the administrative regulations of PSP available at 37 Pa. Code \u00a7\u00a7 33.102-33.113.</ref>\n\n== Concealed carry and transport ==\nIndividuals in Pennsylvania are permitted to open carry firearms as long as the firearm is in plain view. When concealing a firearm, individuals must obtain a License To Carry Firearms from the local sheriffs' office. An individual must have a License To Carry Firearms to carry a handgun in a vehicle in Pennsylvania, Long guns are not allowed to be transported loaded.&nbsp;&nbsp;\n\nIn the only first-class city, Philadelphia, a license is required for both concealed carry, and open carry. A total of 31 states recognized Pennsylvania's license to concealed carry.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.yorkdispatch.com/story/news/politics/2017/10/09/constitutional-carry-pennsylvania-challenged-gun-control-advocates/735599001/|title='Constitutional carry' in Pennsylvania challenged by gun control advocates|work=York Dispatch|access-date=2017-12-07|language=en}}</ref>\n\nWhen transporting firearms in Pennsylvania without a Concealed Carry Permit, the firearm and ammunition must be in two separate containers within the vehicle.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nTo apply for a license to carry in Pennsylvania, individuals must be at least 21 years of age. The application process requires submitting the&nbsp;Pennsylvania License to Carry Firearms application to the sheriff of the county in which they reside. Individuals who are not residents of Pennsylvania but are 21 years of age or older may submit the Application for a Pennsylvania License to Carry Firearms to any Pennsylvania County Sheriff's office along with the required fee.&nbsp;<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.psp.pa.gov/firearms-information/Pages/Carrying-Firearms-in-Pennsylvania.aspx|title=Carrying Firearms in Pennsylvania|website=www.psp.pa.gov|language=en-us|access-date=2017-12-06}}</ref>\n\nFirearms are prohibited from certain places, including federal court facilities; all other court facilities must provide a locker to secure firearms while conducting business within the court facility as per 18 Pa.C.S 913 (e). Concealed carry on school property used to be an unsettled area of the law with many in law enforcement arguing that the practice is absolutely prohibited and firearms right supporters arguing that 18 Pa.C.S. 912(c) permits those who have a concealed carry license to carry on school grounds as an \"other lawful purpose.\" On February 16, 2017, the [[Superior Court of Pennsylvania|Superior Court]] ruled in the case of ''Commonwealth v. Goslin'' that the \"other lawful purpose\" clause is a valid defense for people who are otherwise carrying a weapon legally on school grounds regardless of any connection to a school activity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.princelaw.com/2017/02/16/the-goslin-decisions-impact-on-possessing-weapons-on-school-property/|title=The Goslin Decision's Impact on Possessing Weapons on School Property|last=Prince|first=Joshua|last2=Esq.|date=2017-02-16|website=Prince Law Offices, P.C.|access-date=2017-06-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.handgunlaw.us/documents/PASupremeCtCarryOnSchoolProperty.pdf|title=Commonwealth v. Goslin}}</ref> Carrying a handgun on public streets and public property of Philadelphia, or in a vehicle anywhere in the state, or concealed on or about one's person anywhere in the state is prohibited without a \"License To Carry Firearms\" (LTCF) or a license or permit issued by another state which is honored by Pennsylvania for that purpose.<ref name=LCAV-PA>[http://smartgunlaws.org/pennsylvania-state-law-summary/ \"Pennsylvania State Law Summary\"], Law Center to Prevent Gun Violence. Retrieved January 2, 2013.</ref><ref name=NRA-ILA-PA>[https://www.nraila.org/gun-laws/state-gun-laws/pennsylvania/ \"State Gun Laws: Pennsylvania\"], National Rifle Association \u2013 Institute for Legislative Action. Retrieved December 27, 2015.</ref> A LTCF is generally not required to openly carry a firearm on or about one's person, except in a vehicle or in Philadelphia, or during a declared State of Emergency.<ref name=\"pafoa-open-carry\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pafoa.org/law/carrying-firearms/open-carry|title=Pennsylvania Firearm Owners Association \u2013 Open Carry|date=2007-10-02|publisher=Pafoa.org|accessdate=2012-05-22}}</ref> \nA bill proposed in September 2014 would allow teachers and school employees to carry guns.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyitem.com/news/state/article_7db6a8d4-d559-5526-8f6f-1760c7f9a2f3.html|title=Response mixed on bill to let teachers carry guns|last1=Gautz|first1=Chris|publisher=The Daily Item}}</ref>\n\nPennsylvania [[shall issue]] a LTCF to resident and non-resident applicants if no good cause exists to deny the license. Non-resident applicants must first obtain a license from their home state, unless their home state does not issue licenses.<ref name=\"LCAV-PA\" /><ref name=\"NRA-ILA-PA\" />\n\n== Laws and regulations ==\nArticle 1, section 21 of the [[Constitution of Pennsylvania]] states, \"The right of the citizens to bear arms in defense of themselves and the State shall not be questioned.\"<ref>[http://www.legis.state.pa.us/cfdocs/legis/LI/consCheck.cfm?txtType=HTM&ttl=00&div=0&chpt=1 \"The Constitution of Pennsylvania\"]. Pennsylvania General Assembly. Retrieved January 17, 2018.</ref>\n\nPennsylvania has state preemption for regulation of the lawful ownership, possession, transfer or transportation of firearms, ammunition, or ammunition components. That is, only state laws, not local laws, can regulate those matters.<ref name=\"LCAV-PA\"/><ref name=\"NRA-ILA-PA\"/>\n\nMost items that are required to be registered under the National Firearms Act such as machine guns, suppressors, short barreled rifles and shotguns, are prohibited in Pennsylvania as \"offensive weapons\" unless they are registered under the NFA.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThere are no regulating laws for the sale, purchase, or possession of ammunition. Use of armor-piercing ammunition for criminal activities is specifically prohibited by statute.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.legis.state.pa.us/cfdocs/legis/LI/consCheck.cfm?txtType=HTM&ttl=18&div=0&chpt=61&sctn=21&subsctn=0&mobile_choice=suppress|title=Title 18|last=Center|first=Legislativate Data Processing|website=The official website for the Pennsylvania General Assembly.|language=en|access-date=2018-11-24}}</ref> \n\nPennsylvania law requires that information received by the [[Pennsylvania State Police]] pursuant to a sale is destroyed within 72 hours of the completion of the background check.<ref name=\"LCAV-PA\" /><ref name=\"NRA-ILA-PA\" /> The [http://www.pafoa.org Pennsylvania Firearm Owners Association] notes that the [[Pennsylvania State Police]] nonetheless keep a \"sales database\" of all handguns purchased within the state.<ref name=\"pafoa-pa-sales-database\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pafoa.org/law#faq-do-i-have-to-register-my-guns|title=Pennsylvania Firearm/Gun Law|date=2007-10-02|publisher=Pafoa.org|accessdate=2012-07-09}}</ref> The database was challenged based on what was asserted as the unambiguous text of the statute, specifically \"nothing... ...shall be construed to allow any government or law enforcement agency or any agent thereof to create, maintain or operate any registry of firearm ownership within this Commonwealth\" (full statute text above), the Pennsylvania Supreme Court nonetheless ruled in ''Allegheny County Sportsmen's League v. Rendell'', 860 A.2d 10\n(Pa. 2004), that Pennsylvania's database of handgun sales is not prohibited by state law because the registration was only of handgun sales and not of all guns.<ref name=\"LCAV-REGISTRATION\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lcav.org/content/registration_firearms.pdf|title=LCAV. Registration of Firearms. In Regulating Guns in America: An Evaluation and Comparative Analysis of Federal, State, and Selected Local Gun Laws (2008). Retrieved July 8, 2011.|date=|accessdate=2012-05-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120406205718/http://www.lcav.org/content/registration_firearms.pdf|archive-date=April 6, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Law of Pennsylvania]]\n* [[Uniform Firearms Act]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Gun laws in the United States (by state)}}\n\n[[Category:Pennsylvania law]]\n[[Category:United States gun laws by state|Pennsylvania]]\n", "name_user": "73.79.230.240", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eLaws and regulations)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gun_laws_in_Pennsylvania"}
{"title_page": "Great Chinese Famine", "text_new": "{{about|the famine of 1959\u20131961|other famines in Chinese history|List of famines in China}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox famine\n| famine_name      = <!-----Overrides {{PAGENAME}}, do not use without careful consideration)----->\n| famine_name_in_local = \u4e09\u5e74\u5927\u9965\u8352\n| image_1        = \n| image_title_1  = \n| image_width_1  = 250<!-----The default image size is 126px or 252px depending on the number of images. You can use this parameter to override the default size.----->\n| image_2         = <!-----2nd image----->\n| image_title_2   = <!-----Title for 2nd image----->\n| image_width_2   = <!-----The default image size is 126px or 252px depending on the number of images. You can use this parameter to override the default size.------>\n| country         = [[People's Republic of China]]\n| location        = [[Mainland China]]\n| coordinates     = <!-----(use {{coord}})----->\n| period          = 1959\u20131961\n| excess_mortality= <!-----Deaths directly due to famine starvation----->\n| from_disease    = <!-----Indirect famine deaths from subsequent diseases----->\n| total_deaths    = {{plainlist|\n*15 million (government statistics)\n*15 to 30 million (some scholarly estimates)<ref>Holmes, Leslie. ''Communism: A Very Short Introduction'' ([[Oxford University Press]] 2009). {{ISBN|978-0-19-955154-5}}. p. 32 \"Most estimates of the number of Chinese dead are in the range of 15 to 30 million.\"</ref>\n*At least 45 million (Dik\u00f6tter)}}\n| death_rate      = <!-----Death rate---->\n| observations    = Considered China's most devastating catastrophe by [[Frank Dik\u00f6tter]]. A part of the [[Great Leap Forward]] campaign.\n| theory          =\n| relief          = \n| food_situation  = \n| demographics    = <!-----Example: population declined by 10% due to mortality or 5% of the people emigrated, etc----->\n| consequences    = Termination of the Great Leap Forward campaign\n| memorial        = <!-- links to website? -->\n| preceded        =\n| succeeded       =\n| footnotes       = <!-----Test footnote----->\n}}{{Short description|Famine killing millions in China, stemming from Great Leap Forward and climate}}{{History of the People's Republic of China}}\n\nThe '''Great Chinese Famine''' ({{zh|s=\u4e09\u5e74\u5927\u9965\u8352}}, \"three years of famine\") was a period in the [[People's Republic of China]] (PRC) between the years 1959 and 1961 ([[Great Leap Forward]]) characterized by widespread [[famine]]. The Great Chinese famine is widely regarded as the deadliest famine and one of the greatest man-made disasters in human history, with an estimated death toll due to starvation ranges in the tens of millions.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Smil|first=Vaclav|date=1999-12-18|title=China's great famine: 40 years later|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1127087/|journal=BMJ : British Medical Journal|volume=319|issue=7225|pages=1619\u20131621|issn=0959-8138|pmc=1127087|pmid=10600969}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gr\u00e1da|first=Cormac \u00d3|date=2007|title=Making Famine History|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/27646746|journal=Journal of Economic Literature|volume=45|issue=1|pages=5\u201338|issn=0022-0515}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=MENG|first=XIN|last2=QIAN|first2=NANCY|last3=YARED|first3=PIERRE|date=2015|title=The Institutional Causes of China\u2019s Great Famine, 1959\u20131961|url=https://www0.gsb.columbia.edu/faculty/pyared/papers/famines.pdf|journal=Review of Economic Studies|volume=82|pages=1568\u20131611|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hasell|first=Joe|last2=Roser|first2=Max|date=2013-10-10|title=Famines|url=https://ourworldindata.org/famines|journal=Our World in Data}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dartmouth.edu/~crossley/HIST5.03/FILES/OHMC_DIkotter.pdf|title=Mao's Great Famine: Ways of Living, Ways of Dying|last=Dik\u00f6tter|first=Frank|date=|website=Dartmouth University|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|last=Mirsky|first=Jonathan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/09/books/review/tombstone-the-great-chinese-famine-1958-1962-by-yang-jisheng.html|title=Unnatural Disaster|date=2012-12-07|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-22|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Branigan|first=Tania|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/jan/01/china-great-famine-book-tombstone|title=China's Great Famine: the true story|date=2013-01-01|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-22|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/programmes/ajeats/2016/01/china-great-famine-mission-expose-truth-160106100552321.html|title=China's Great Famine: A mission to expose the truth|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://qz.com/633457/charted-chinas-great-famine-according-to-yang-jisheng-a-journalist-who-lived-through-it/|title=Charted: China\u2019s Great Famine, according to Yang Jisheng, a journalist who lived through it|last=Huang|first=Zheping|website=Quartz|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> The major contributing factors to the famine were the policies of the [[Great Leap Forward]] and [[People's commune]], in addition to some natural disasters such as droughts which took place during the period.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> In 1961, [[Liu Shaoqi]], the [[President of the People's Republic of China|2nd Chairman of PRC]] attributed the famine 30% to natural disasters and 70% to man-made policies (\"\u4e09\u5206\u5929\u707e, \u4e03\u5206\u4eba\u7978\").<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cpc.people.com.cn/GB/64162/64172/85037/85039/5898093.html|title=\u5218\u5c11\u5947\u201c\u4e09\u5206\u5929\u707e\uff0c\u4e03\u5206\u4eba\u7978\u201d\u63d0\u6cd5\u7684\u7531\u6765--\u4e2d\u56fd\u5171\u4ea7\u515a\u65b0\u95fb--\u4e2d\u56fd\u5171\u4ea7\u515a\u65b0\u95fb\u7f51|last=|first=|date=|website=cpc.people.com.cn|language=zh|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cpc.people.com.cn/GB/64162/64172/85037/85039/5898130.html|title=\u5218\u5c11\u5947\u201c\u4e09\u5206\u5929\u707e\uff0c\u4e03\u5206\u4eba\u7978\u201d\u63d0\u6cd5\u7684\u7531\u6765(2)--\u4e2d\u56fd\u5171\u4ea7\u515a\u65b0\u95fb--\u4e2d\u56fd\u5171\u4ea7\u515a\u65b0\u95fb\u7f51|last=|first=|date=|website=cpc.people.com.cn|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> \n\n== Terminology ==\nThe famine in China has been known by many names, inside China and out.\n\nIn China, it is known as the \"Three Years of Great Famine\" ({{zh|s=\u4e09\u5e74\u5927\u9965\u8352|t=\u4e09\u5e74\u5927\u9951\u8352|p=S\u0101nni\u00e1n d\u00e0 j\u012bhu\u0101ng}}).  The [[government of the People's Republic of China]] called it \"Three Years of Natural Disasters\" ({{zh|s=\u4e09\u5e74\u81ea\u7136\u707e\u5bb3|t=\u4e09\u5e74\u81ea\u7136\u707d\u5bb3|p=S\u0101nni\u00e1n z\u00ecr\u00e1n z\u0101ih\u00e0i}}) before the 1980s, and later renamed it the \"Three Years of Difficulty\" ({{zh|s=\u4e09\u5e74\u56f0\u96be\u65f6\u671f|t=\u4e09\u5e74\u56f0\u96e3\u6642\u671f|p=S\u0101nni\u00e1n k\u00f9nn\u00e1n sh\u00edq\u012b}})<ref name=\"Songster-2004\">{{cite book|last=Songster|first=Edith Elena|title=A Natural Place for Nationalism: The Wanglang Nature Reserve and the Emergence of the Giant Panda as a National Icon|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MSyIXwAACAAJ|accessdate=18 January 2018|year=2004|publisher=University of California, San Diego|oclc=607612241|type=thesis}}</ref>{{page needed|date=January 2018}}.{{better source|date=January 2018}}<ref>{{cite journal |last1=M. |first1=J. |title=New (approved) assessments The great famine |language=English |url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/analects/2013/09/new-approved-assessments |journal=The Economist |date=17 February 2015 |location=Beijing |accessdate=18 January 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180120153221/https://www.economist.com/blogs/analects/2013/09/new-approved-assessments |archive-date=20 January 2018 |url-status=live }} citing {{cite book |last=Dik\u00f6tter |first=Frank |title=The Tragedy of Liberation: A History of the Chinese Revolution 1945\u20131957 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JuvlBQAAQBAJ |accessdate=18 January 2018 |date=17 February 2015 |publisher=Bloomsbury Press |location=London |isbn=978-1-62040-349-5 |oclc=881092774}}{{page needed|date=January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Extent of the famine==\n\n=== Production drop ===\n[[File:Birth rate in China.svg|thumb|upright=2|{{center|Birth and death rate in China}}]]\n[[File:China-pyramid-1982.svg|thumb|Chinese [[population pyramid]] from 1982, displaying a huge shortage of people born in 1959\u201361, reflecting the high [[infant mortality]] and low birth rate during the period]]\n\nThe radically harmful changes in farming organization and policies coincided with adverse weather patterns, including droughts and floods. As a result, year over year grain production dropped in China. The harvest was down by 15% in 1959. By 1960, it was at 70% of its 1958 level. There was no recovery until 1962, after the Great Leap Forward was declared over by the Central government.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lin|first1=Justin Yifu|last2=Yang|first2=Dennis Tao|year=2000|title=Food Availability, Entitlements and the Chinese Famine of 1959\u201361|journal=[[The Economic Journal]]|publisher=[[Royal Economic Society]]|volume=110|issue=460|page=143|doi=10.1111/1468-0297.00494}}<!--|accessdate=14 November 2012--></ref> According to the China Statistical Yearbook (1984), crop production decreased from 200 million tons in 1958 to 143.5 million tons in 1960.\n\n=== Death toll ===\nDue to lack of food and incentive to marry at that time, the population was about 658,590,000 in 1961, about 13,480,000 less than the population of 1959. Birth rate decreased from 2.922% (1958) to 2.086% (1960) and death rate increased from 1.198% (1958) to 2.543% (1960), while the average numbers for 1962\u20131965 are about 4% and 1%, respectively.\n\nAccording to government statistics, there were 15 million excess deaths in this period.  Unofficial estimates vary, but scholars have estimated the number of famine victims to be between 20 and 43 million.<ref name=\"xiz\">Peng Xizhe (\u5f6d\u5e0c\u54f2), \"Demographic Consequences of the Great Leap Forward in China's Provinces,\" ''Population and Development Review'' 13, no. 4 (1987), 639\u201370.<br />For a summary of other estimates, please refer to ''Necrometrics'' [http://necrometrics.com/20c5m.htm] {{Webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/69erJ2JTC?url=http://necrometrics.com/20c5m.htm|date=4 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nYu Dehong, the secretary of a party official in [[Xinyang]] in 1959 and 1960, stated,\n<blockquote>I went to one village and saw 100 corpses, then another village and another 100 corpses. No one paid attention to them. People said that dogs were eating the bodies. Not true, I said. The dogs had long ago been eaten by the people.<ref name=\"trans\" /></blockquote>\n\nIt is widely believed that the government seriously under-reported death tolls: Lu Baoguo, a [[Xinhua]] reporter in Xinyang, told [[Yang Jisheng (historian)|Yang Jisheng]] of why he never reported on his experience:\n<blockquote>In the second half of 1959, I took a long-distance bus from Xinyang to [[Luoshan]] and [[Gushi County|Gushi]]. Out of the window, I saw one corpse after another in the ditches. On the bus, no one dared to mention the dead. In one county, [[Guangshan]], one-third of the people had died. Although there were dead people everywhere, the local leaders enjoyed good meals and fine liquor. ... I had seen people who had told the truth being destroyed. Did I dare to write it?<ref name=\"trans\" /></blockquote>\n\nSome Western analysts, such as [[Patricia Buckley Ebrey]], estimate that about 20\u201340 million people had died of starvation caused by bad government policies and natural disasters {{citation needed|reason=No linked source makes this claim hard to verify, as the mentioned author has published many different works on China.|date=August 2019}}. J. Banister estimates that this number is about 23 million. Li Chengrui, a former minister of the [[National Bureau of Statistics of China]], estimated 22 million (1998). His estimation was based on [[Ansley J. Coale]] and Jiang Zhenghua's estimation of 27 million. Cao Shuji estimated 32.5 million. The aforementioned [[Yang Jisheng (historian)|Yang Jisheng]] (2008) estimated the death toll at 36 million.<ref name=\"hunger\">[http://en.chinaelections.org/newsinfo.asp?newsid=18328 \"A hunger for the truth: A new book, banned on the mainland, is becoming the definitive account of the Great Famine.\"], chinaelections.org, 7 July 2008 {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120210190821/http://en.chinaelections.org/newsinfo.asp?newsid=18328|date=10 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nHong Kong-based historian [[Frank Dik\u00f6tter]] (2010) estimated that, at minimum, 45 million people died from starvation, overwork and state violence during the Great Leap, claiming his findings to be based on access to recently opened local and provincial party archives.<ref name=\"Dikotter333\" /><ref name=\"indepedent\">{{cite news|last=Akbar|first=Arifa|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/news/maos-great-leap-forward-killed-45-million-in-four-years-2081630.html|title=Mao's Great Leap Forward 'killed 45 million in four years'|date=17 September 2010|work=The Independent|accessdate=20 September 2010|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101029150409/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/news/maos-great-leap-forward-killed-45-million-in-four-years-2081630.html|archive-date=29 October 2010|location=London}}</ref> His study also stressed that state violence exacerbated the death toll.  Dik\u00f6tter claimed that at least 2.5 million of the victims were beaten or tortured to death.<ref>Dik\u00f6tter, Frank. ''[[Mao's Great Famine]]: The History of China's Most Devastating Catastrophe, 1958\u201362.'' Walker & Company, 2010. p. 298. {{ISBN|0-8027-7768-6}}</ref> His approach to the documents, as well as his claim to be the first author to use them, however, have been questioned by other scholars.<ref>Dillon, Michael. \"Collective Responsibility\" ''The Times Literary Supplement'' 7 January (2011), p. 13.</ref>\n\nChinese journalist [[Yang Jisheng (historian)|Yang Jisheng]] concluded there were 36 million deaths due to starvation, while another 40 million others failed to be born, so that \"China's total population loss during the Great Famine then comes to 76 million.\"<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite news|last=Mirsky|first=Jonathan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/09/books/review/tombstone-the-great-chinese-famine-1958-1962-by-yang-jisheng.html?nl=books&emc=edit_bk_20121207|title=Unnatural Disaster: 'Tombstone: The Great Chinese Famine, 1958\u20131962,' by Yang Jisheng|date=9 December 2012|newspaper=The New York Times Sunday Book Review|accessdate=7 December 2012|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121208064043/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/09/books/review/tombstone-the-great-chinese-famine-1958-1962-by-yang-jisheng.html?nl=books&emc=edit_bk_20121207|archive-date=8 December 2012|page=BR22}}</ref>\n\n[[Utsa Patnaik]] writes \"The figure of 30 million has passed into popular folklore...The fact that 19 million of them never existed because they were never born in the first place, is not conveyed by the formulation.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.socialisteconomist.com/2018/11/ideological-statistics-inflated-death.html?m=1|title=Ideological Statistics: Inflated Death Rates of China's Famine, the Russian one Ignored}}</ref> She criticized the equating of China's \"missing millions\" with famine deaths, rather than people who were never born due to declining birth rates. Patnaik concluded that the figures were ideologically derived in attempts to discredit communism, while similar excessive deaths in 1990s Russia, following the collapse of the USSR, were routinely ignored.\n\nDik\u00f6tter provides a graphic example of what happened to a family after one member was caught stealing some food:\n\n<blockquote>Liu Desheng, guilty of poaching a sweet potato, was covered in urine ... He, his wife, and his son were also forced into a heap of excrement. Then tongs were used to prise his mouth open after he refused to swallow excrement. He died three weeks later.<ref>Issac Stone Fish. [http://www.newsweek.com/2010/09/26/mao-s-great-famine.html Greeting Misery With Violence] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110119201202/http://www.newsweek.com/2010/09/26/mao-s-great-famine.html|date=19 January 2011}}. [[Newsweek]]. 26 September 2010.</ref></blockquote>\n\nThere are widespread oral reports, and some official documentation, of [[cannibalism]] being practised in various forms, as a result of the famine.<ref name=\"bern97\">{{cite news|last=Bernstein|first=Richard|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9A0CE3D71E3DF936A35751C0A961958260|title=Horror of a Hidden Chinese Famine|date=5 February 1997|work=[[New York Times]]|access-date=8 February 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090305072906/http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9A0CE3D71E3DF936A35751C0A961958260|archive-date=5 March 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"becker\">{{cite book|last=Becker|first=Jasper|url=https://archive.org/details/hungryghostsmaos00beck|title=Hungry Ghosts: Mao's Secret Famine|publisher=Free Press|year=1997|isbn=978-0-68483457-3|url-access=registration}}</ref>{{rp|352}}{{efn|The title of [[#CITEREFBecker1998|Becker's book]] is a reference to [[Hungry ghosts]] in Chinese religion.}}<ref>{{cite book|last=Dik\u00f6tter|first=Frank|title=Mao's Great Famine: The History of China's Most Devastating Catastrophe, 1958\u20131962|year=2010|isbn=978-0-80277768-3|pages=320\u2013323|chapter=36. Cannibalism}}</ref> Due to the scale of the famine, the resulting cannibalism has been described as \"on a scale unprecedented in the history of the 20th century\".<ref name=\"bern97\" /><ref name=\"becker\" />{{page needed|date=February 2018}}\n\n==Causes of the famine==\nThe great famine was caused by a combination of natural disasters, widespread drought in farming regions, social pressure, economic mismanagement, and radical agricultural changes in regulations imposed by the government. \n\n=== Great Leap Forward ===\n{{Main Article|Great Leap Forward}}\n\nIn July 1959, the [[Yellow River]] flooded in [[East China]]. According to the Disaster Center, the flood directly killed, either through starvation from crop failure or drowning, an estimated 2 million people, while other areas were affected in other ways as well.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.disastercenter.com/disaster/TOP100K.html|title=The Most Deadly 100 Natural Disasters of the 20th Century|access-date=4 July 2005|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171110082733/http://www.disastercenter.com/disaster/TOP100K.html|archive-date=10 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Frank Dik\u00f6tter]] argues that most floods were not due to unusual weather, but to massive, poorly planned and poorly executed irrigation works which were part of the [[Great Leap Forward]].<ref name=\"Dikotter333\">Dik\u00f6tter, Frank. ''Mao's Great Famine: The History of China's Most Devastating Catastrophe, 1958\u201362.'' Walker & Company, 2010. p. 333. {{ISBN|0-8027-7768-6}}</ref> At this time, China was building thousands of kilometers of new irrigation canals in an attempt to move water from wet areas to areas that were experiencing drought.\n\n[[Mao Zedong]], Chinese Communist Party Chairman, introduced drastic changes in farming policy which prohibited farm ownership. Failure to abide by the policies led to punishment. The social pressure imposed on the citizens in terms of farming and business, which the government controlled, led to state instability. Owing to the laws passed during the period and the [[Great Leap Forward]] during 1958\u20131962, and according to an analysis by journalist Yang Jisheng, about 36 million people died of starvation in this period.<ref>Jisheng, Yang \"Tombstone: The Great Chinese Famine, 1958\u20131962\". Book Review. ''New York Times''. Dec, 2012. 3 March 2013. https://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/09/books/review/tombstone-the-great-chinese-famine-1958-1962-by-yang-jisheng.html {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170124011617/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/09/books/review/tombstone-the-great-chinese-famine-1958-1962-by-yang-jisheng.html |date=24 January 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==== People's commune ====\n[[File:People's commune canteen.jpg|thumb|The canteen of [[people's commune]].]]\nDuring the Great Leap Forward, farming was organized into [[People's commune|communes]] and the cultivation of privately owned plots forbidden. Iron and steel production was identified as a key requirement for economic advancement. Millions of peasants were ordered away from agricultural work to join the iron and steel production workforce.\n\nIn 2008, [[Yang Jisheng (historian)|Yang Jisheng]] would summarize the effect of the focus on production targets :\n<blockquote>In [[Xinyang]], people starved at the doors of the grain warehouses. As they died, they shouted, \"Communist Party, Chairman Mao, save us\". If the granaries of [[Henan]] and [[Hebei]] had been opened, no one need have died. As people were dying in large numbers around them, officials did not think to save them. Their only concern was how to fulfill the delivery of grain.<ref name=trans>Translation from [http://en.chinaelections.org/newsinfo.asp?newsid=18328 \"A hunger for the truth: A new book, banned on the mainland, is becoming the definitive account of the Great Famine.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120210190821/http://en.chinaelections.org/newsinfo.asp?newsid=18328 |date=10 February 2012 }}, chinaelections.org, 7 July 2008 of content from [[Yang Jisheng (historian)|Yang Jisheng]], ''\u5893\u7891 \uff0d\uff0d\u4e2d\u570b\u516d\u5341\u5e74\u4ee3\u5927\u9951\u8352\u7d00\u5be6 (Mu Bei \u2013 Zhong Guo Liu Shi Nian Dai Da Ji Huang Ji Shi)'', Hong Kong: Cosmos Books (Tian Di Tu Shu), 2008, {{ISBN|9789882119093}} {{in lang|zh}}</ref></blockquote>In fact, the topic of the People's commune and the degree in which it influenced the famine holds contention in regards to its overall influence. Each region dealt with the famine differently and timelines of the famine are not uniform across China. The overarching argument is that excessive eating that took place in the mess halls directly led to a worsening of the famine and that if excessive eating did not take place then, \"the worst of the Great Leap Famine could still have been avoided in mid-1959.\"<ref>{{cite book|author=Dali L. Yang|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VmLuoAkMKrkC|title=Calamity and Reform in China: State, Rural Society, and Institutional Change Since the Great Leap Famine|publisher=Stanford University Press|year=1996|isbn=978-0-8047-3470-7|page=55}}</ref> However, dire hunger did not set into Da Fo until 1960<ref>{{cite book|author=Ralph Thaxton|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=14A1qPQOgQMC|title=Catastrophe and Contention in Rural China: Mao's Great Leap Forward Famine and the Origins of Righteous Resistance in Da Fo Village|date=5 May 2008|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-72230-8|page=125}}</ref> and the public dining hall participation rate was found to be meaningless in terms of causation in [[Anhui]] and [[Jiangxi]].<ref>{{cite book|author1=Kimberley Ens Manning|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aHPTn2Rq9IUC|title=Eating Bitterness: New Perspectives on China's Great Leap Forward and Famine|author2=Felix Wemheuer|author3=Chen Yixin|date=1 January 2011|publisher=UBC Press|isbn=978-0-7748-5955-4|page=220|chapter=Under the Same Maoist Sky : Accounting for Death Rate Discrepancies in Anhui and Jiangxi}}</ref> \n\nEconomists Xin Meng [[Nancy Qian]] and Pierre Yared show that, much like [[Amartya Sen]]'s earlier claims, aggregate production was sufficient for avoiding famine and that the famine was caused by over-procurement and poor distribution within the country. They show that unlike most other famines, there was surprisingly more deaths in places that produced more food per capita and argue that the inflexibility in the centrally planned food procurement system explains at least half of the famine mortality.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Meng|first=Xin|last2=Qian|first2=Nancy|last3=Yared|first3=Pierre|date=2015-10-01|title=The Institutional Causes of China's Great Famine, 1959\u20131961|url=https://academic.oup.com/restud/article/82/4/1568/2607347|journal=The Review of Economic Studies|volume=82|issue=4|pages=1568\u20131611|doi=10.1093/restud/rdv016|issn=0034-6527}}</ref> Economic historians James Kung and Shuo Chen show that there was more over procurement in places where politicians faced more competition.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kung|first=James Kai-Sing|last2=Chen|first2=Shuo|date=February 2011|title=The Tragedy of the Nomenklatura: Career Incentives and Political Radicalism during China's Great Leap Famine|journal=American Political Science Review|volume=105|issue=1|pages=27\u201345|doi=10.1017/S0003055410000626|issn=1537-5943}}</ref>\n\n==== Agricultural techniques ====\nAlong with [[collectivization]], the central government decreed several changes in agricultural techniques that would be based on the [[Lysenkoism|ideas]] of later-discredited Russian agronomist [[Trofim Lysenko]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The People's Republic of China, 1949\u201376|edition=second|first=Michael|last=Lynch|location=London|publisher=Hodder Education|year=2008|page=57}}</ref> One of these ideas was close planting, whereby the density of seedlings was at first tripled and then doubled again. The theory was that plants of the same species would not compete with each other. In natural cycles they did fully compete, which actually stunted growth and resulted in lower yields.\n\nAnother implemented policy (known as \"[[deep plowing]]\") was based on the ideas of Lysenko's colleague [[Terentiy Maltsev]], who encouraged peasants across China to eschew normal [[plowing]] depths of 15\u201320 centimeters and instead plow extremely deeply into the soil (1 to 2 meters). The deep plowing theory stated that the most fertile soil was deep in the earth, and plowing unusually deep would allow extra strong root growth. However, in shallow soil, useless rocks, soil, and sand were driven up instead, burying the fertile topsoil and severely stunting seedling growth.\n\n==== Four Pest Campaign ====\n[[File:Tree-Sparrow-2009-16-02.jpg|thumb|upright=1.1|The [[Eurasian tree sparrow]] was the most notable target of the [[Four Pests Campaign]]]]\n\nAdditionally, in the [[Four Pests Campaign]], citizens were called upon to destroy sparrows and other wild birds that ate crop seeds, in order to protect fields. Pest birds were shot down or scared away from landing until dropping in exhaustion. This system failed and resulted in an explosion of the vermin population, especially crop-eating insects, which consequently had no predators.\n\n<br />\n\n==== Illusion of superabundance ====\n{{Confusing|section|date=May 2019}}The Party began to export excessive amounts of grain from regions in 1957 under the Great Leap Forward. However, the production of grain throughout China was decreasing from 1957\u20131961. In areas, such as Sichuan Province, the grain collected was decreasing from 1958\u20131961,<ref name=\"Jisheng2012\">{{cite book|author=Yang Jisheng|title=Tombstone: The Great Chinese Famine, 1958\u20131962|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nadqrYU10eMC|date=30 October 2012|publisher=Farrar, Straus and Giroux|isbn=978-0-374-27793-2|page=240}}</ref> yet the numbers being reported kept increasing.  Beijing believed, \"In 1960 state granaries would have 50 billion ''[[Chinese units of measurement|jin]]'' of grain,\" when they actually contained 12.7 billion ''jin.''<ref>{{cite book|author1=Kimberley Ens Manning|author2=Felix Wemheuer|author3=Gao Hua|title=Eating Bitterness: New Perspectives on China's Great Leap Forward and Famine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aHPTn2Rq9IUC|date=1 January 2011|publisher=UBC Press|isbn=978-0-7748-5955-4|page=177|chapter=Food Augmentation Methods and Food Substitutes during the Great Famine}}</ref> Within Da Fo \"food ''output'' by and large did not decline, but there was an astonishing loss of food ''availability'' associated with Maoist state appropriation\"<ref name=\"Thaxton2008\">{{cite book|author=Ralph Thaxton|title=Catastrophe and Contention in Rural China: Mao's Great Leap Forward Famine and the Origins of Righteous Resistance in Da Fo Village|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=14A1qPQOgQMC|date=5 May 2008|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-72230-8|page=128}}</ref> and the grain yield in [[Gansu]] declined by 4,273,000 tonnes from 1957 to 1961.<ref>{{cite book|author=Yang Jisheng|title=Tombstone: The Great Chinese Famine, 1958-1962|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nadqrYU10eMC|date=30 October 2012|publisher=Farrar, Straus and Giroux|isbn=978-0-374-27793-2|page=126}}</ref> This series of events resulted in the illusion of superabundance, in which the Party believed that they had an excess amount of grain they could access; but, the Party was also unaware that crop yields were in fact lower than average.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\nThe effects of the illusion of superabundance were significant, leaving historians to argue it to being the cause of much of the starvation throughout China. Yang Dali states that there were three main consequences from the illusion of superabundance:<ref>{{cite book|author=Dali L. Yang|title=Calamity and Reform in China: State, Rural Society, and Institutional Change Since the Great Leap Famine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VmLuoAkMKrkC|year=1996|publisher=Stanford University Press|isbn=978-0-8047-3470-7|page=65}}</ref> <blockquote>First, it led to planners to shift lands from grain to economic crops, such as cotton, sugarcane, and beets, and divert huge numbers agricultural laborers into industrial sectors, fueling state demand for procured grain from the countryside. Second, it prompted the Chinese leadership, especially [[Zhou Enlai]], to speed up grain exports to secure more foreign currency to purchase capital goods needed for industrialization. Finally, the illusion of superabundance made the adoption of the commune mess halls seem rational at the time. All these changes, of course, contributed to the rapid exhaustion of grain supplies.</blockquote>\n\n=== More policies from central government ===\nGovernment policies that were implemented, particularly the [[Three Red Banners]] and the [[Socialist Education Movement]] (SEM), proved to be ideologically detrimental to the increasing famine.  The Three Red Banners of the CCP \"sparked the fanaticism of 1958\"  and the implementation of the General Line, one of the three banners which told people to, \"go all out, aim high, and build socialism with greater, better, and more economical results\" directly links to the pressures officials felt when reporting a superabundance of grain.<ref>{{cite book|author=Yang Jisheng|title=Tombstone: The Great Chinese Famine, 1958\u20131962|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nadqrYU10eMC|date=30 October 2012|publisher=Farrar, Straus and Giroux|isbn=978-0-374-27793-2|page=87}}</ref> The SEM, established in 1957, also led to the severity of the famine in many ways, including the illusion of superabundance. Once the exaggerations of crop yields from the [[Mass line|General Line]] were reported, \"no one dared to 'dash cold water'\" on further reports.<ref>{{cite book|author=Yang Jisheng|title=Tombstone: The Great Chinese Famine, 1958\u20131962|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nadqrYU10eMC|date=30 October 2012|publisher=Farrar, Straus and Giroux|isbn=978-0-374-27793-2|page=99}}</ref> The SEM also led to the establishment of conspiratory thoughts in which the peasants were believed to be pretending to be hungry in order to sabotage the state grain purchase.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Kimberley Ens Manning|author2=Felix Wemheuer|title=Eating Bitterness: New Perspectives on China's Great Leap Forward and Famine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aHPTn2Rq9IUC|date=1 January 2011|publisher=UBC Press|isbn=978-0-7748-5955-4|page=127|chapter=\"The Grain Problem is an Ideological Problem\" : Discourses of Hunger in the 1957 Socialist Education Campaign}}</ref>\n\n=== Power relations in local government ===\n[[File:1957 Mao Zedong on airplane.jpg|thumb|upright=1.1|left|[[Mao Zedong]] on an airplane, 1957]]\n\nLocal governments had just as much, if not more, influence on the famine than did agriculture and higher forms of government. As the Great Leap Forward progressed, many provincial leaders began to extend their reach by working closely with Mao and higher Party leaders; which, in turn resulted in these provincial leaders abusing power that they did not actually have.<ref>{{cite book|author=Dali L. Yang|title=Calamity and Reform in China: State, Rural Society, and Institutional Change Since the Great Leap Famine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VmLuoAkMKrkC|year=1996|publisher=Stanford University Press|isbn=978-0-8047-3470-7|page=31}}</ref> This abuse of power caused passivity on the local level.  Local landlords began \"denouncing any opposition as 'conservative rightism,'\" which is defined broadly as anything anti-communist.<ref>{{cite book|author=Frank Dik\u00f6tter|title=Mao's Great Famine: The History of China's Most Devastating Catastrophe, 1958\u20131962|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5NsMWCHDStQC|date=1 October 2010|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|isbn=978-0-8027-7928-1|page=2}}</ref> With the ongoing conspiratorial theories revolving around peasants, it was seen that saving extra grain for a family to eat, the belief that the Great Leap Forward should not be implemented, or merely not working hard enough could all be seen as forms of 'conservative rightism.' This hatred led to peasants becoming unable to openly speak on collectivization and state grain purchase. By enforcing such passivity at a local level while there already was passivity at an official level, speaking and acting against the famine became a seemingly impossible task.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Kimberley Ens Manning|author2=Felix Wemheuer|title=Eating Bitterness: New Perspectives on China's Great Leap Forward and Famine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aHPTn2Rq9IUC|date=1 January 2011|publisher=UBC Press|isbn=978-0-7748-5955-4|page=110|chapter=\"The Grain Problem is an Ideological Problem\" : Discourses of Hunger in the 1957 Socialist Education Campaign}}</ref>\n\nThe influence of local government in the famine can be seen in the comparison between the provinces of Anhui and Jiangxi. Anhui, having a radical pro-Mao government, was led by [[Zeng Xisheng]] who was \"dictatorial\" with ties to Mao.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Kimberley Ens Manning|author2=Felix Wemheuer|title=Eating Bitterness: New Perspectives on China's Great Leap Forward and Famine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aHPTn2Rq9IUC|date=1 January 2011|publisher=UBC Press|isbn=978-0-7748-5955-4|pages=212\u2013213|chapter=Under the Same Maoist Sky : Accounting for Death Rate Discrepancies in Anhui and Jiangxi}}</ref> Zeng firmly believed in the Great Leap Forward and tried to hold relationships with higher officials rather than keep close local ties. Zeng proposed agricultural projects without consulting colleagues which caused Anhui's agriculture to fail terribly.  Zhang Kaifan, a party secretary and deputy-governor of the province, heard rumours of a famine breaking out in Anhui and disagreed with many of Zeng's policies. Zeng reported Zhang to Mao for such speculations which led Mao to label Zhang \"a member of the 'Peng Dehuai anti-Party military clique,'\" resulting in him being purged from the local party. Zeng was unable to report of the famine when it became an emergency situation as this would prove his hypocrisy and caused him to become a \"blatant political radical who almost single-handedly damaged Anhui.\"<ref>{{cite book|author1=Kimberley Ens Manning|author2=Felix Wemheuer|title=Eating Bitterness: New Perspectives on China's Great Leap Forward and Famine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aHPTn2Rq9IUC|date=1 January 2011|publisher=UBC Press|isbn=978-0-7748-5955-4|pages=213|chapter=Under the Same Maoist Sky : Accounting for Death Rate Discrepancies in Anhui and Jiangxi}}</ref>\n\nJiangxi encountered a situation almost opposite to that of Anhui. The leaders of Jiangxi publicly opposed some of the Great Leap programs, quietly made themselves unavailable, and even appeared to take a passive attitude towards the Maoist economy. As the leaders worked collaboratively among themselves, they also worked with the local population as well. By being able to create an environment in which the Great Leap Forward did not become fully implemented, the Jiangxi government \"did their best to minimize damage\u2026\" These findings concluded that much of the severity of the famine came down to provincial leaders and their responsibility for their regions.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Kimberley Ens Manning|author2=Felix Wemheuer|title=Eating Bitterness: New Perspectives on China's Great Leap Forward and Famine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aHPTn2Rq9IUC|date=1 January 2011|publisher=UBC Press|isbn=978-0-7748-5955-4|pages=216\u2013218|chapter=Under the Same Maoist Sky : Accounting for Death Rate Discrepancies in Anhui and Jiangxi}}</ref>\n\n=== Natural disasters ===\nIn 1960, at least some degree of drought and other bad weather affected 55% of cultivated land, while an estimated 60% of agricultural land in northern China received no rain at all.<ref name=\"Atimes\">{{cite news|last=Liu|first=Henry C K|url=http://www.atimes.com/atimes/China/FD01Ad04.html|title=Part 2: The Great Leap Forward not all bad|date=1 April 2004|work=[[Asia Times]] online|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050204085928/http://www.atimes.com/atimes/China/FD01Ad04.html|archive-date=4 February 2005}}</ref> The [[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]] yearbooks from 1958 to 1962 also reported abnormal weather, followed by droughts and floods based on Chinese government sources. This included {{convert|760|mm|in}} of rain in [[Hong Kong]] across five days in June 1959, part of a pattern that hit all of [[Southern China]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Fred Harding|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0h2gDLv3MOEC&pg=PA381|title=Breast Cancer: Cause, Prevention, Cure|publisher=Tekline Publishing|year=2006|isbn=978-0-9554221-0-2|page=381}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath ==\n\n=== Initial cover-ups ===\nLocal party leaders, for their part, conspired to cover up shortfalls and reassign blame in order to protect their own lives and positions.{{citation needed|reason=They did cover up shortfalls and invent numbers, but the second part of this needs a citation.|date=January 2018}}\n\nIn visits to [[Henan province]] in 1958, Mao observed what local officials claimed was increases in crop yield of one thousand to three thousand percent achieved, supposedly, in massive 24-hour pushes organized by the officials which they called \"sputnik launches\".  But the numbers were faked, and so were the fields that Mao observed, which had been carefully prepared in advance of Mao's visit by local officials, who removed shoots of grain from various fields and carefully transplanted them into a field prepared especially for Mao, which appeared to be a bumper crop.<ref name=\"becker\" />{{rp|122}}\n\nThe local officials became trapped by these sham demonstrations to Mao, and exhorted the peasants to reach unattainable goals, by \"deep ploughing and close planting\", and other techniques. This ended up making things much worse, the crop failed completely, leaving barren fields. No one was in a position to challenge Mao's ideas as incorrect, so peasants pulled out their bedding and coats into the fields, added seeds and water, and after they sprouted, buried the materials under the soil once the seedlings were high enough.<ref name=\"becker\" />{{rp|122}}\n\nIn a similar manner to the massive Soviet-created famine in Ukraine (the [[Holodomor]]), doctors were prohibited from listing \"starvation\" as a cause of death on death certificates. This kind of deception was far from uncommon; a famous [[propaganda]] picture from the famine shows Chinese children from [[Shandong]] province ostensibly standing atop a field of wheat, so densely grown that it could apparently support their weight. In reality, they were standing on a bench concealed beneath the plants, and the \"field\" was again entirely composed of individually transplanted stalks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RKNEdojrsMo|title=Mao's Great Famine|last=International School History|date=21 January 2015|accessdate=19 September 2018|via=YouTube|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181030033514/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RKNEdojrsMo|archive-date=30 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>[http://www.disasterhistory.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/Standing-on-Grain-Propaganda-1959.jpg Aforementioned propaganda photo. ]\n\n=== Reflections ===\nIn 1962, [[Liu Shaoqi]], then [[President of the People's Republic of China]], concluded after 44 days of field research in villages of [[Hunan]] that the reasons for the famine were 30% natural disaster and 70% human error.<ref>[http://cpc.people.com.cn/GB/64162/64172/85037/85039/5898093.html \u5218\u5c11\u5947\"\u4e09\u5206\u5929\u707e\uff0c\u4e03\u5206\u4eba\u7978\"\u63d0\u6cd5\u7684\u7531\u6765] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121214040606/http://cpc.people.com.cn/GB/64162/64172/85037/85039/5898093.html |date=14 December 2012 }}, Selection of the Party History (\u515a\u53f2\u535a\u91c7), 22 June 2007, Accessed Sept 1, 2018, CPC News. {{in lang|zh-Hans}}</ref>\n\n[[Amartya Sen]] puts this famine in a global context, arguing that lack of democracy is the major culprit: \"Indeed, no substantial famine has ever occurred in a democratic country\u2014no matter how poor.\" He adds that it is \"hard to imagine that anything like this could have happened in a country that goes to the polls regularly and that has an independent press. During that terrible calamity the government faced no pressure from newspapers, which were controlled, and none from opposition parties, which were absent.\"<ref name=\"Sen1999\">{{cite book|author=Amartya Kumar Sen|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Qm8HtpFHYecC|title=Development as freedom|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=1999|isbn=978-0-19-289330-7|accessdate=14 April 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140103042841/http://books.google.com/books?id=Qm8HtpFHYecC|archive-date=3 January 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> On the other hand, Sen points out that the numbers of \"excess mortality\" in India often surpass what they were in China during 1958\u20131961.<ref>Wiener, Jon. [https://books.google.com/books?id=1KiD069CPsUC&pg=PA38 \"How We Forgot the Cold War. A Historical Journey across America\"] University of California Press, 2012, p. 38.</ref> Sen argued that \"Despite the gigantic size of excess mortality in the Chinese famine, the extra mortality in India from regular deprivation in normal times vastly overshadows the former...India seems to manage to fill its cupboard with more skeletons every eight years than China put there in its years of shame.\"\n\nUntil the early 1980s, the [[Government of the People's Republic of China|Chinese government]]'s stance, reflected by the name \"Three Years of Natural Disasters\", was that the famine was largely a result of a series of natural disasters compounded by several planning errors. Researchers outside China argued that massive institutional and policy changes that accompanied the Great Leap Forward were the key factors in the famine, or at least worsened nature-induced disasters.<ref>{{cite video|title=China: A Century of Revolution|date=1997|people=Sue Williams (director), Howard Sharp (editor), [[Will Lyman]] (narrator)|publisher=WinStar Home Entertainment}}</ref><ref>{{citation|title=Encyclopedia of Population|volume=1|pages=388\u2013390|year=2003|editor-last=Demeny|editor-first=Paul|contribution=Famine in China|place=New York|publisher=Macmillan Reference|editor2-last=McNicoll|editor2-first=Geoffrey}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Northern Chinese Famine of 1876\u201379]]\n* [[Chinese famine of 1928\u201330]]\n* [[Chinese famine of 1942\u201343]]\n* [[Four Pests Campaign]]\n* [[Holodomor]]\n* [[Bengal famine of 1943]]\n* ''[[Hungry Ghosts: Mao's Secret Famine]]\n* ''[[Mao's Great Famine]]''\n* [[70,000 Character Petition]]\n* [[Mass killings under communist regimes]]\n\n== References ==\n\n=== Notes ===\n{{Notelist}}\n\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n{{refbegin}}\n* Ashton, Basil, Kenneth Hill, Alan Piazza, Robin Zeitz, \"Famine in China, 1958\u201361\", ''Population and Development Review,'' Vol. 10, No. 4. (Dec. 1984), pp.&nbsp;613\u2013645.\n* Banister, J. \"Analysis of Recent Data on the Population of China\", ''Population and Development,'' Vol. 10, No. 2, 1984.\n* {{cite book |last1=Becker |first1=Jasper |authorlink1=Jasper Becker |year=1998 |title=Hungry Ghosts: Mao's Secret Famine |publisher=[[Henry Holt and Company|Holt]] |series=A Holt paperback : history |isbn=0-8050-5668-8 |oclc=985077206 |ref=harv }}\n* Cao Shuji, \"The Deaths of China's Population and Its Contributing Factors during 1959\u20131961\". ''China's Population Science'' (Jan. 2005) (In Chinese).\n* ''China Statistical Yearbook'' (1984), edited by State Statistical Bureau. China Statistical Publishing House, 1984. pp.&nbsp;83, 141, 190.\n* ''China Statistical Yearbook'' (1991), edited by State Statistical Bureau. China Statistical Publishing House, 1991.\n* ''China Population Statistical Yearbook'' (1985), edited by State Statistical Bureau. China Statistical Bureau Publishing House, 1985.\n* [[Ansley J. Coale|Coale, Ansley J.]], ''Rapid Population Change in China, 1952\u20131982'', [[National Academy Press]], Washington, D.C., 1984.\n* [[Frank Dik\u00f6tter|Dik\u00f6tter, Frank]]. ''[[Mao's Great Famine|Mao's Great Famine: The History of China's Most Devastating Catastrophe, 1958\u201362]]''. [[Walker & Company]], 2010. {{ISBN|0-8027-7768-6}}.\n* Gao. Mobo (2007). ''Gao Village: Rural Life in Modern China''. [[University of Hawaii Press]]. {{ISBN|978-0-8248-3192-9}}.\n* Gao. Mobo (2008). ''The Battle for China's Past''. [[Pluto Press]]. {{ISBN|978-0-7453-2780-8}}.\n* Jiang Zhenghua (\u8523\u6b63\u83ef)\uff0c \"Method and Result of China Population Dynamic Estimation\", Academic Report of Xi'a University, 1986(3). pp.&nbsp;46, 84.\n* Li Chengrui(\u674e\u6210\u745e): Population Change Caused by The Great Leap Movement, Demographic Study, No.1, 1998 pp.&nbsp;97\u2013111\n* Li. Minqi (2008). ''The Rise of China and the Demise of the Capitalist World Economy''. [[Monthly Review Press]]. {{ISBN|978-1-58367-182-5}}\n* Peng Xizhe, \"Demographic Consequences of the Great Leap Forward in China's Provinces\", ''Population and Development Review,'' Vol. 13, No. 4. (Dec. 1987), pp.&nbsp;639\u2013670\n* Thaxton. Ralph A. Jr (2008). ''Catastrophe and Contention in Rural China: Mao's Great Leap Forward Famine and the Origins of Righteous Resistance in Da Fo Village''. [[Cambridge University Press]]. {{ISBN|0-521-72230-6}}\n* Yang, Dali. ''Calamity and Reform in China: State, Rural Society and Institutional Change since the Great Leap Famine''. Stanford University Press, 1996.\n* [[Yang Jisheng (historian)|Yang Jisheng]]. ''Tombstone (Mu Bei&nbsp;\u2013 Zhong Guo Liu Shi Nian Dai Da Ji Huang Ji Shi).'' Cosmos Books (Tian Di Tu Shu), [[Hong Kong]] 2008.\n* [[Yang Jisheng (historian)|Yang Jisheng]]. \"Tombstone: An Account of Chinese Famine in the 1960s\" (\u5893\u7891 \uff0d \u4e2d\u570b\u516d\u5341\u5e74\u4ee3\u5927\u9951\u8352\u7d00\u5be6 (Mubei \u2013 Zhongguo Liushi Niandai Da Jihuang Jishi), Hong Kong: Cosmos Books (Tiandi Tushu), 2008, {{ISBN|978-988-211-909-3}} {{in lang|zh}}. By 2010, it was appearing under the title: \u5893\u7891: \u4e00\u4e5d\u4e94\u516b-\u4e00\u4e5d\u516d\u4e8c\u5e74\u4e2d\u570b\u5927\u9951\u8352\u7d00\u5be6 (Mubei: Yi Jiu Wu Ba \u2013 Yi Jiu Liu Er Nian Zhongguo Da Jihuang Shiji) (\"Tombstone: An Account of Chinese Famine From 1958\u20131962\").\n* [[Yang Jisheng (historian)|Yang Jisheng]]. Tombstone: The Untold Story of Mao's Great Famine, Yang Jisheng, Translators: Stacy Mosher, Guo Jian, Publisher: Allen Lane (30 October 2012), {{ISBN|978-184-614-518-6}} (English translation of the above work)\n** Translated into English and abridged. Yang Jisheng, ''Tombstone: The Great Chinese Famine, 1958\u20131962'', Farrar, Straus and Giroux (30 October 2012), hardcover, 656 pp., {{ISBN|0374277931}}, {{ISBN|978-0374277932}}\n* Official Chinese statistics, shown as a graph. {{citation|url=http://www.iiasa.ac.at/Research/LUC/ChinaFood/data/pop/pop_10.htm |publisher=[[International Institute for Applied Systems Analysis]] (IIASA) |work=Land Use Systems Group (LUC)|location=[[Austria]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050904001002/http://www.iiasa.ac.at/Research/LUC/ChinaFood/data/pop/pop_10.htm |archivedate=4 September 2005|title=Data \u2013 Population Growth}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Portal bar|1950s|1960s|China}}\n\n[[Category:1959 disasters]]\n[[Category:1959 in China]]\n[[Category:1960 disasters]]\n[[Category:1960 in China]]\n[[Category:1961 disasters]]\n[[Category:1961 in China]]\n[[Category:Famines in China]]\n[[Category:Incidents of cannibalism]]\n[[Category:Man-made disasters in China]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the famine of 1959\u20131961|other famines in Chinese history|List of famines in China}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox famine\n| famine_name      = <!-----Overrides {{PAGENAME}}, do not use without careful consideration)----->\n| famine_name_in_local = \u4e09\u5e74\u5927\u9965\u8352\n| image_1        = \n| image_title_1  = \n| image_width_1  = 250<!-----The default image size is 126px or 252px depending on the number of images. You can use this parameter to override the default size.----->\n| image_2         = <!-----2nd image----->\n| image_title_2   = <!-----Title for 2nd image----->\n| image_width_2   = <!-----The default image size is 126px or 252px depending on the number of images. You can use this parameter to override the default size.------>\n| country         = [[People's Republic of China]]\n| location        = [[Mainland China]]\n| coordinates     = <!-----(use {{coord}})----->\n| period          = 1959\u20131961\n| excess_mortality= <!-----Deaths directly due to famine starvation----->\n| from_disease    = <!-----Indirect famine deaths from subsequent diseases----->\n| total_deaths    = {{plainlist|\n*15 million (government statistics)\n*15 to 30 million (some scholarly estimates)<ref>Holmes, Leslie. ''Communism: A Very Short Introduction'' ([[Oxford University Press]] 2009). {{ISBN|978-0-19-955154-5}}. p. 32 \"Most estimates of the number of Chinese dead are in the range of 15 to 30 million.\"</ref>\n*At least 45 million (Dik\u00f6tter)}}\n| death_rate      = <!-----Death rate---->\n| observations    = Considered China's most devastating catastrophe by [[Frank Dik\u00f6tter]]. A part of the [[Great Leap Forward]] campaign.\n| theory          =\n| relief          = \n| food_situation  = \n| demographics    = <!-----Example: population declined by 10% due to mortality or 5% of the people emigrated, etc----->\n| consequences    = Termination of the Great Leap Forward campaign\n| memorial        = <!-- links to website? -->\n| preceded        =\n| succeeded       =\n| footnotes       = <!-----Test footnote----->\n}}{{Short description|Famine killing millions in China, stemming from Great Leap Forward and climate}}{{History of the People's Republic of China}}\n\nThe '''Great Chinese Famine''' ({{zh|s=\u4e09\u5e74\u5927\u9965\u8352}}, \"three years of famine\") was a period in the [[People's Republic of China]] (PRC) between the years 1959 and 1961 ([[Great Leap Forward]]) characterized by widespread [[famine]]. The Great Chinese famine is widely regarded as the deadliest famine and one of the greatest man-made disasters in human history, with an estimated death toll due to starvation ranges in the tens of millions.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Smil|first=Vaclav|date=1999-12-18|title=China's great famine: 40 years later|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1127087/|journal=BMJ : British Medical Journal|volume=319|issue=7225|pages=1619\u20131621|issn=0959-8138|pmc=1127087|pmid=10600969}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gr\u00e1da|first=Cormac \u00d3|date=2007|title=Making Famine History|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/27646746|journal=Journal of Economic Literature|volume=45|issue=1|pages=5\u201338|issn=0022-0515}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=MENG|first=XIN|last2=QIAN|first2=NANCY|last3=YARED|first3=PIERRE|date=2015|title=The Institutional Causes of China\u2019s Great Famine, 1959\u20131961|url=https://www0.gsb.columbia.edu/faculty/pyared/papers/famines.pdf|journal=Review of Economic Studies|volume=82|pages=1568\u20131611|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hasell|first=Joe|last2=Roser|first2=Max|date=2013-10-10|title=Famines|url=https://ourworldindata.org/famines|journal=Our World in Data}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dartmouth.edu/~crossley/HIST5.03/FILES/OHMC_DIkotter.pdf|title=Mao's Great Famine: Ways of Living, Ways of Dying|last=Dik\u00f6tter|first=Frank|date=|website=Dartmouth University|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|last=Mirsky|first=Jonathan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/09/books/review/tombstone-the-great-chinese-famine-1958-1962-by-yang-jisheng.html|title=Unnatural Disaster|date=2012-12-07|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-22|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Branigan|first=Tania|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/jan/01/china-great-famine-book-tombstone|title=China's Great Famine: the true story|date=2013-01-01|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-22|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/programmes/ajeats/2016/01/china-great-famine-mission-expose-truth-160106100552321.html|title=China's Great Famine: A mission to expose the truth|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://qz.com/633457/charted-chinas-great-famine-according-to-yang-jisheng-a-journalist-who-lived-through-it/|title=Charted: China\u2019s Great Famine, according to Yang Jisheng, a journalist who lived through it|last=Huang|first=Zheping|website=Quartz|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> The major contributing factors to the famine were the policies of the [[Great Leap Forward]] and [[People's commune]], in addition to some natural disasters such as droughts which took place during the period.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> In 1961, [[Liu Shaoqi]], the [[President of the People's Republic of China|2nd Chairman of PRC]] attributed the famine 30% to natural disasters and 70% to man-made policies (\"\u4e09\u5206\u5929\u707e, \u4e03\u5206\u4eba\u7978\").<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cpc.people.com.cn/GB/64162/64172/85037/85039/5898093.html|title=\u5218\u5c11\u5947\u201c\u4e09\u5206\u5929\u707e\uff0c\u4e03\u5206\u4eba\u7978\u201d\u63d0\u6cd5\u7684\u7531\u6765--\u4e2d\u56fd\u5171\u4ea7\u515a\u65b0\u95fb--\u4e2d\u56fd\u5171\u4ea7\u515a\u65b0\u95fb\u7f51|last=|first=|date=|website=cpc.people.com.cn|language=zh|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cpc.people.com.cn/GB/64162/64172/85037/85039/5898130.html|title=\u5218\u5c11\u5947\u201c\u4e09\u5206\u5929\u707e\uff0c\u4e03\u5206\u4eba\u7978\u201d\u63d0\u6cd5\u7684\u7531\u6765(2)--\u4e2d\u56fd\u5171\u4ea7\u515a\u65b0\u95fb--\u4e2d\u56fd\u5171\u4ea7\u515a\u65b0\u95fb\u7f51|last=|first=|date=|website=cpc.people.com.cn|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> \n\n== Terminology ==\nThe famine in China has been known by many names, inside China and out.\n\nIn China, it is known as the \"Three Years of Great Famine\" ({{zh|s=\u4e09\u5e74\u5927\u9965\u8352|t=\u4e09\u5e74\u5927\u9951\u8352|p=S\u0101nni\u00e1n d\u00e0 j\u012bhu\u0101ng}}).  The [[government of the People's Republic of China]] called it \"Three Years of Natural Disasters\" ({{zh|s=\u4e09\u5e74\u81ea\u7136\u707e\u5bb3|t=\u4e09\u5e74\u81ea\u7136\u707d\u5bb3|p=S\u0101nni\u00e1n z\u00ecr\u00e1n z\u0101ih\u00e0i}}) before the 1980s, and later renamed it the \"Three Years of Difficulty\" ({{zh|s=\u4e09\u5e74\u56f0\u96be\u65f6\u671f|t=\u4e09\u5e74\u56f0\u96e3\u6642\u671f|p=S\u0101nni\u00e1n k\u00f9nn\u00e1n sh\u00edq\u012b}})<ref name=\"Songster-2004\">{{cite book|last=Songster|first=Edith Elena|title=A Natural Place for Nationalism: The Wanglang Nature Reserve and the Emergence of the Giant Panda as a National Icon|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MSyIXwAACAAJ|accessdate=18 January 2018|year=2004|publisher=University of California, San Diego|oclc=607612241|type=thesis}}</ref>{{page needed|date=January 2018}}.{{better source|date=January 2018}}<ref>{{cite journal |last1=M. |first1=J. |title=New (approved) assessments The great famine |language=English |url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/analects/2013/09/new-approved-assessments |journal=The Economist |date=17 February 2015 |location=Beijing |accessdate=18 January 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180120153221/https://www.economist.com/blogs/analects/2013/09/new-approved-assessments |archive-date=20 January 2018 |url-status=live }} citing {{cite book |last=Dik\u00f6tter |first=Frank |title=The Tragedy of Liberation: A History of the Chinese Revolution 1945\u20131957 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JuvlBQAAQBAJ |accessdate=18 January 2018 |date=17 February 2015 |publisher=Bloomsbury Press |location=London |isbn=978-1-62040-349-5 |oclc=881092774}}{{page needed|date=January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Extent of the famine==\n\n=== Production drop ===\n[[File:Birth rate in China.svg|thumb|upright=2|{{center|Birth and death rate in China}}]]\n[[File:China-pyramid-1982.svg|thumb|Chinese [[population pyramid]] from 1982, displaying a huge shortage of people born in 1959\u201361, reflecting the high [[infant mortality]] and low birth rate during the period]]\n\nThe radically harmful changes in farming organization and policies coincided with adverse weather patterns, including droughts and floods. As a result, year over year grain production dropped in China. The harvest was down by 15% in 1959. By 1960, it was at 70% of its 1958 level. There was no recovery until 1962, after the Great Leap Forward was declared over by the Central government.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lin|first1=Justin Yifu|last2=Yang|first2=Dennis Tao|year=2000|title=Food Availability, Entitlements and the Chinese Famine of 1959\u201361|journal=[[The Economic Journal]]|publisher=[[Royal Economic Society]]|volume=110|issue=460|page=143|doi=10.1111/1468-0297.00494}}<!--|accessdate=14 November 2012--></ref> According to the China Statistical Yearbook (1984), crop production decreased from 200 million tons in 1958 to 143.5 million tons in 1960.\n\n=== Death toll ===\nDue to lack of food and incentive to marry at that time, the population was about 658,590,000 in 1961, about 13,480,000 less than the population of 1959. Birth rate decreased from 2.922% (1958) to 2.086% (1960) and death rate increased from 1.198% (1958) to 2.543% (1960), while the average numbers for 1962\u20131965 are about 4% and 1%, respectively.\n\nAccording to government statistics, there were 15 million excess deaths in this period.  Unofficial estimates vary, but scholars have estimated the number of famine victims to be between 20 and 43 million.<ref name=\"xiz\">Peng Xizhe (\u5f6d\u5e0c\u54f2), \"Demographic Consequences of the Great Leap Forward in China's Provinces,\" ''Population and Development Review'' 13, no. 4 (1987), 639\u201370.<br />For a summary of other estimates, please refer to ''Necrometrics'' [http://necrometrics.com/20c5m.htm] {{Webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/69erJ2JTC?url=http://necrometrics.com/20c5m.htm|date=4 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nYu Dehong, the secretary of a party official in [[Xinyang]] in 1959 and 1960, stated,\n<blockquote>I went to one village and saw 100 corpses, then another village and another 100 corpses. No one paid attention to them. People said that dogs were eating the bodies. Not true, I said. The dogs had long ago been eaten by the people.<ref name=\"trans\" /></blockquote>\n\nIt is widely believed that the government seriously under-reported death tolls: Lu Baoguo, a [[Xinhua]] reporter in Xinyang, told [[Yang Jisheng (historian)|Yang Jisheng]] of why he never reported on his experience:\n<blockquote>In the second half of 1959, I took a long-distance bus from Xinyang to [[Luoshan]] and [[Gushi County|Gushi]]. Out of the window, I saw one corpse after another in the ditches. On the bus, no one dared to mention the dead. In one county, [[Guangshan]], one-third of the people had died. Although there were dead people everywhere, the local leaders enjoyed good meals and fine liquor. ... I had seen people who had told the truth being destroyed. Did I dare to write it?<ref name=\"trans\" /></blockquote>\n\nSome Western analysts, such as [[Patricia Buckley Ebrey]], estimate that about 20\u201340 million people had died of starvation caused by bad government policies and natural disasters {{citation needed|reason=No linked source makes this claim hard to verify, as the mentioned author has published many different works on China.|date=August 2019}}. J. Banister estimates that this number is about 23 million. Li Chengrui, a former minister of the [[National Bureau of Statistics of China]], estimated 22 million (1998). His estimation was based on [[Ansley J. Coale]] and Jiang Zhenghua's estimation of 27 million. Cao Shuji estimated 32.5 million. The aforementioned [[Yang Jisheng (historian)|Yang Jisheng]] (2008) estimated the death toll at 36 million.<ref name=\"hunger\">[http://en.chinaelections.org/newsinfo.asp?newsid=18328 \"A hunger for the truth: A new book, banned on the mainland, is becoming the definitive account of the Great Famine.\"], chinaelections.org, 7 July 2008 {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120210190821/http://en.chinaelections.org/newsinfo.asp?newsid=18328|date=10 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nHong Kong-based historian [[Frank Dik\u00f6tter]] (2010) estimated that, at minimum, 45 million people died from starvation, overwork and state violence during the Great Leap, claiming his findings to be based on access to recently opened local and provincial party archives.<ref name=\"Dikotter333\" /><ref name=\"indepedent\">{{cite news|last=Akbar|first=Arifa|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/news/maos-great-leap-forward-killed-45-million-in-four-years-2081630.html|title=Mao's Great Leap Forward 'killed 45 million in four years'|date=17 September 2010|work=The Independent|accessdate=20 September 2010|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101029150409/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/news/maos-great-leap-forward-killed-45-million-in-four-years-2081630.html|archive-date=29 October 2010|location=London}}</ref> His study also stressed that state violence exacerbated the death toll.  Dik\u00f6tter claimed that at least 2.5 million of the victims were beaten or tortured to death.<ref>Dik\u00f6tter, Frank. ''[[Mao's Great Famine]]: The History of China's Most Devastating Catastrophe, 1958\u201362.'' Walker & Company, 2010. p. 298. {{ISBN|0-8027-7768-6}}</ref> His approach to the documents, as well as his claim to be the first author to use them, however, have been questioned by other scholars.<ref>Dillon, Michael. \"Collective Responsibility\" ''The Times Literary Supplement'' 7 January (2011), p. 13.</ref>\n\nChinese journalist [[Yang Jisheng (historian)|Yang Jisheng]] concluded there were 36 million deaths due to starvation, while another 40 million others failed to be born, so that \"China's total population loss during the Great Famine then comes to 76 million.\"<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite news|last=Mirsky|first=Jonathan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/09/books/review/tombstone-the-great-chinese-famine-1958-1962-by-yang-jisheng.html?nl=books&emc=edit_bk_20121207|title=Unnatural Disaster: 'Tombstone: The Great Chinese Famine, 1958\u20131962,' by Yang Jisheng|date=9 December 2012|newspaper=The New York Times Sunday Book Review|accessdate=7 December 2012|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121208064043/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/09/books/review/tombstone-the-great-chinese-famine-1958-1962-by-yang-jisheng.html?nl=books&emc=edit_bk_20121207|archive-date=8 December 2012|page=BR22}}</ref>\n\n[[Utsa Patnaik]] writes \"The figure of 30 million has passed into popular folklore...The fact that 19 million of them never existed because they were never born in the first place, is not conveyed by the formulation.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.socialisteconomist.com/2018/11/ideological-statistics-inflated-death.html?m=1|title=Ideological Statistics: Inflated Death Rates of China's Famine, the Russian one Ignored}}</ref> She criticized the equating of China's \"missing millions\" with famine deaths, rather than people who were never born due to declining birth rates. Patnaik concluded that the figures were ideologically derived in attempts to discredit communism, while similar excessive deaths in 1990s Russia, following the collapse of the USSR, were routinely ignored.\n\nDik\u00f6tter provides a graphic example of what happened to a family after one member was caught stealing some food:\n\n<blockquote>Liu Desheng, guilty of poaching a sweet potato, was covered in urine ... He, his wife, and his son were also forced into a heap of excrement. Then tongs were used to prise his mouth open after he refused to swallow excrement. He died three weeks later.<ref>Issac Stone Fish. [http://www.newsweek.com/2010/09/26/mao-s-great-famine.html Greeting Misery With Violence] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110119201202/http://www.newsweek.com/2010/09/26/mao-s-great-famine.html|date=19 January 2011}}. [[Newsweek]]. 26 September 2010.</ref></blockquote>\n\nThere are widespread oral reports, and some official documentation, of [[cannibalism]] being practised in various forms, as a result of the famine.<ref name=\"bern97\">{{cite news|last=Bernstein|first=Richard|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9A0CE3D71E3DF936A35751C0A961958260|title=Horror of a Hidden Chinese Famine|date=5 February 1997|work=[[New York Times]]|access-date=8 February 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090305072906/http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9A0CE3D71E3DF936A35751C0A961958260|archive-date=5 March 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"becker\">{{cite book|last=Becker|first=Jasper|url=https://archive.org/details/hungryghostsmaos00beck|title=Hungry Ghosts: Mao's Secret Famine|publisher=Free Press|year=1997|isbn=978-0-68483457-3|url-access=registration}}</ref>{{rp|352}}{{efn|The title of [[#CITEREFBecker1998|Becker's book]] is a reference to [[Hungry ghosts]] in Chinese religion.}}<ref>{{cite book|last=Dik\u00f6tter|first=Frank|title=Mao's Great Famine: The History of China's Most Devastating Catastrophe, 1958\u20131962|year=2010|isbn=978-0-80277768-3|pages=320\u2013323|chapter=36. Cannibalism}}</ref> Due to the scale of the famine, the resulting cannibalism has been described as \"on a scale unprecedented in the history of the 20th century\".<ref name=\"bern97\" /><ref name=\"becker\" />{{page needed|date=February 2018}}\n\n==Causes of the famine==\nThe great famine was caused by a combination of natural disasters, widespread drought in farming regions, social pressure, economic mismanagement, and radical agricultural changes in regulations imposed by the government. \n\n=== Great Leap Forward ===\n{{Main Article|Great Leap Forward}}\n\nIn July 1959, the [[Yellow River]] flooded in [[East China]]. According to the Disaster Center, the flood directly killed, either through starvation from crop failure or drowning, an estimated 2 million people, while other areas were affected in other ways as well.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.disastercenter.com/disaster/TOP100K.html|title=The Most Deadly 100 Natural Disasters of the 20th Century|access-date=4 July 2005|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171110082733/http://www.disastercenter.com/disaster/TOP100K.html|archive-date=10 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Frank Dik\u00f6tter]] argues that most floods were not due to unusual weather, but to massive, poorly planned and poorly executed irrigation works which were part of the [[Great Leap Forward]].<ref name=\"Dikotter333\">Dik\u00f6tter, Frank. ''Mao's Great Famine: The History of China's Most Devastating Catastrophe, 1958\u201362.'' Walker & Company, 2010. p. 333. {{ISBN|0-8027-7768-6}}</ref> At this time, China was building thousands of kilometers of new irrigation canals in an attempt to move water from wet areas to areas that were experiencing drought.\n\n[[Mao Zedong]], Chinese Communist Party Chairman, introduced drastic changes in farming policy which prohibited farm ownership. Failure to abide by the policies led to punishment. The social pressure imposed on the citizens in terms of farming and business, which the government controlled, led to state instability. Owing to the laws passed during the period and the [[Great Leap Forward]] during 1958\u20131962, and according to an analysis by journalist Yang Jisheng, about 36 million people died of starvation in this period.<ref>Jisheng, Yang \"Tombstone: The Great Chinese Famine, 1958\u20131962\". Book Review. ''New York Times''. Dec, 2012. 3 March 2013. https://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/09/books/review/tombstone-the-great-chinese-famine-1958-1962-by-yang-jisheng.html {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170124011617/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/09/books/review/tombstone-the-great-chinese-famine-1958-1962-by-yang-jisheng.html |date=24 January 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==== People's commune ====\n[[File:People's commune canteen.jpg|thumb|The canteen of [[people's commune]].]]\nDuring the Great Leap Forward, farming was organized into [[People's commune|communes]] and the cultivation of privately owned plots forbidden. Iron and steel production was identified as a key requirement for economic advancement. Millions of peasants were ordered away from agricultural work to join the iron and steel production workforce.\n\n[[Yang Jisheng (historian)|Yang Jisheng]] would summarize the effect of the focus on production targets in 2008:\n<blockquote>In [[Xinyang]], people starved at the doors of the grain warehouses. As they died, they shouted, \"Communist Party, Chairman Mao, save us\". If the granaries of [[Henan]] and [[Hebei]] had been opened, no one need have died. As people were dying in large numbers around them, officials did not think to save them. Their only concern was how to fulfill the delivery of grain.<ref name=trans>Translation from [http://en.chinaelections.org/newsinfo.asp?newsid=18328 \"A hunger for the truth: A new book, banned on the mainland, is becoming the definitive account of the Great Famine.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120210190821/http://en.chinaelections.org/newsinfo.asp?newsid=18328 |date=10 February 2012 }}, chinaelections.org, 7 July 2008 of content from [[Yang Jisheng (historian)|Yang Jisheng]], ''\u5893\u7891 \uff0d\uff0d\u4e2d\u570b\u516d\u5341\u5e74\u4ee3\u5927\u9951\u8352\u7d00\u5be6 (Mu Bei \u2013 Zhong Guo Liu Shi Nian Dai Da Ji Huang Ji Shi)'', Hong Kong: Cosmos Books (Tian Di Tu Shu), 2008, {{ISBN|9789882119093}} {{in lang|zh}}</ref></blockquote>The topic of the People's commune and the degree in which it influenced the famine holds contention in regards to its overall influence. Each region dealt with the famine differently and timelines of the famine are not uniform across China. The overarching argument is that excessive eating that took place in the mess halls directly led to a worsening of the famine and that if excessive eating did not take place then, \"the worst of the Great Leap Famine could still have been avoided in mid-1959.\"<ref>{{cite book|author=Dali L. Yang|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VmLuoAkMKrkC|title=Calamity and Reform in China: State, Rural Society, and Institutional Change Since the Great Leap Famine|publisher=Stanford University Press|year=1996|isbn=978-0-8047-3470-7|page=55}}</ref> However, dire hunger did not set into Da Fo until 1960<ref>{{cite book|author=Ralph Thaxton|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=14A1qPQOgQMC|title=Catastrophe and Contention in Rural China: Mao's Great Leap Forward Famine and the Origins of Righteous Resistance in Da Fo Village|date=5 May 2008|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-72230-8|page=125}}</ref> and the public dining hall participation rate was found to be meaningless in terms of causation in [[Anhui]] and [[Jiangxi]].<ref>{{cite book|author1=Kimberley Ens Manning|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aHPTn2Rq9IUC|title=Eating Bitterness: New Perspectives on China's Great Leap Forward and Famine|author2=Felix Wemheuer|author3=Chen Yixin|date=1 January 2011|publisher=UBC Press|isbn=978-0-7748-5955-4|page=220|chapter=Under the Same Maoist Sky : Accounting for Death Rate Discrepancies in Anhui and Jiangxi}}</ref> \n\nEconomists Xin Meng [[Nancy Qian]] and Pierre Yared show that, much like [[Amartya Sen]]'s earlier claims, aggregate production was sufficient for avoiding famine and that the famine was caused by over-procurement and poor distribution within the country. They show that unlike most other famines, there was surprisingly more deaths in places that produced more food per capita and argue that the inflexibility in the centrally planned food procurement system explains at least half of the famine mortality.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Meng|first=Xin|last2=Qian|first2=Nancy|last3=Yared|first3=Pierre|date=2015-10-01|title=The Institutional Causes of China's Great Famine, 1959\u20131961|url=https://academic.oup.com/restud/article/82/4/1568/2607347|journal=The Review of Economic Studies|volume=82|issue=4|pages=1568\u20131611|doi=10.1093/restud/rdv016|issn=0034-6527}}</ref> Economic historians James Kung and Shuo Chen show that there was more over procurement in places where politicians faced more competition.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kung|first=James Kai-Sing|last2=Chen|first2=Shuo|date=February 2011|title=The Tragedy of the Nomenklatura: Career Incentives and Political Radicalism during China's Great Leap Famine|journal=American Political Science Review|volume=105|issue=1|pages=27\u201345|doi=10.1017/S0003055410000626|issn=1537-5943}}</ref>\n\n==== Agricultural techniques ====\nAlong with [[collectivization]], the central government decreed several changes in agricultural techniques that would be based on the [[Lysenkoism|ideas]] of later-discredited Russian agronomist [[Trofim Lysenko]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The People's Republic of China, 1949\u201376|edition=second|first=Michael|last=Lynch|location=London|publisher=Hodder Education|year=2008|page=57}}</ref> One of these ideas was close planting, whereby the density of seedlings was at first tripled and then doubled again. The theory was that plants of the same species would not compete with each other. In natural cycles they did fully compete, which actually stunted growth and resulted in lower yields.\n\nAnother implemented policy (known as \"[[deep plowing]]\") was based on the ideas of Lysenko's colleague [[Terentiy Maltsev]], who encouraged peasants across China to eschew normal [[plowing]] depths of 15\u201320 centimeters and instead plow extremely deeply into the soil (1 to 2 meters). The deep plowing theory stated that the most fertile soil was deep in the earth, and plowing unusually deep would allow extra strong root growth. However, in shallow soil, useless rocks, soil, and sand were driven up instead, burying the fertile topsoil and severely stunting seedling growth.\n\n==== Four Pest Campaign ====\n[[File:Tree-Sparrow-2009-16-02.jpg|thumb|upright=1.1|The [[Eurasian tree sparrow]] was the most notable target of the [[Four Pests Campaign]]]]\n\nAdditionally, in the [[Four Pests Campaign]], citizens were called upon to destroy sparrows and other wild birds that ate crop seeds, in order to protect fields. Pest birds were shot down or scared away from landing until dropping in exhaustion. This system failed and resulted in an explosion of the vermin population, especially crop-eating insects, which consequently had no predators.\n\n<br />\n\n==== Illusion of superabundance ====\n{{Confusing|section|date=May 2019}}The Party began to export excessive amounts of grain from regions in 1957 under the Great Leap Forward. However, the production of grain throughout China was decreasing from 1957\u20131961. In areas, such as Sichuan Province, the grain collected was decreasing from 1958\u20131961,<ref name=\"Jisheng2012\">{{cite book|author=Yang Jisheng|title=Tombstone: The Great Chinese Famine, 1958\u20131962|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nadqrYU10eMC|date=30 October 2012|publisher=Farrar, Straus and Giroux|isbn=978-0-374-27793-2|page=240}}</ref> yet the numbers being reported kept increasing.  Beijing believed, \"In 1960 state granaries would have 50 billion ''[[Chinese units of measurement|jin]]'' of grain,\" when they actually contained 12.7 billion ''jin.''<ref>{{cite book|author1=Kimberley Ens Manning|author2=Felix Wemheuer|author3=Gao Hua|title=Eating Bitterness: New Perspectives on China's Great Leap Forward and Famine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aHPTn2Rq9IUC|date=1 January 2011|publisher=UBC Press|isbn=978-0-7748-5955-4|page=177|chapter=Food Augmentation Methods and Food Substitutes during the Great Famine}}</ref> Within Da Fo \"food ''output'' by and large did not decline, but there was an astonishing loss of food ''availability'' associated with Maoist state appropriation\"<ref name=\"Thaxton2008\">{{cite book|author=Ralph Thaxton|title=Catastrophe and Contention in Rural China: Mao's Great Leap Forward Famine and the Origins of Righteous Resistance in Da Fo Village|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=14A1qPQOgQMC|date=5 May 2008|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-72230-8|page=128}}</ref> and the grain yield in [[Gansu]] declined by 4,273,000 tonnes from 1957 to 1961.<ref>{{cite book|author=Yang Jisheng|title=Tombstone: The Great Chinese Famine, 1958-1962|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nadqrYU10eMC|date=30 October 2012|publisher=Farrar, Straus and Giroux|isbn=978-0-374-27793-2|page=126}}</ref> This series of events resulted in the illusion of superabundance, in which the Party believed that they had an excess amount of grain they could access; but, the Party was also unaware that crop yields were in fact lower than average.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\nThe effects of the illusion of superabundance were significant, leaving historians to argue it to being the cause of much of the starvation throughout China. Yang Dali states that there were three main consequences from the illusion of superabundance:<ref>{{cite book|author=Dali L. Yang|title=Calamity and Reform in China: State, Rural Society, and Institutional Change Since the Great Leap Famine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VmLuoAkMKrkC|year=1996|publisher=Stanford University Press|isbn=978-0-8047-3470-7|page=65}}</ref> <blockquote>First, it led to planners to shift lands from grain to economic crops, such as cotton, sugarcane, and beets, and divert huge numbers agricultural laborers into industrial sectors, fueling state demand for procured grain from the countryside. Second, it prompted the Chinese leadership, especially [[Zhou Enlai]], to speed up grain exports to secure more foreign currency to purchase capital goods needed for industrialization. Finally, the illusion of superabundance made the adoption of the commune mess halls seem rational at the time. All these changes, of course, contributed to the rapid exhaustion of grain supplies.</blockquote>\n\n=== More policies from central goverment ===\nGovernment policies that were implemented, particularly the [[Three Red Banners]] and the [[Socialist Education Movement]] (SEM), proved to be ideologically detrimental to the increasing famine.  The Three Red Banners of the CCP \"sparked the fanaticism of 1958\"  and the implementation of the General Line, one of the three banners which told people to, \"go all out, aim high, and build socialism with greater, better, and more economical results\" directly links to the pressures officials felt when reporting a superabundance of grain.<ref>{{cite book|author=Yang Jisheng|title=Tombstone: The Great Chinese Famine, 1958\u20131962|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nadqrYU10eMC|date=30 October 2012|publisher=Farrar, Straus and Giroux|isbn=978-0-374-27793-2|page=87}}</ref> The SEM, established in 1957, also led to the severity of the famine in many ways, including the illusion of superabundance. Once the exaggerations of crop yields from the [[Mass line|General Line]] were reported, \"no one dared to 'dash cold water'\" on further reports.<ref>{{cite book|author=Yang Jisheng|title=Tombstone: The Great Chinese Famine, 1958\u20131962|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nadqrYU10eMC|date=30 October 2012|publisher=Farrar, Straus and Giroux|isbn=978-0-374-27793-2|page=99}}</ref> The SEM also led to the establishment of conspiratory thoughts in which the peasants were believed to be pretending to be hungry in order to sabotage the state grain purchase.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Kimberley Ens Manning|author2=Felix Wemheuer|title=Eating Bitterness: New Perspectives on China's Great Leap Forward and Famine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aHPTn2Rq9IUC|date=1 January 2011|publisher=UBC Press|isbn=978-0-7748-5955-4|page=127|chapter=\"The Grain Problem is an Ideological Problem\" : Discourses of Hunger in the 1957 Socialist Education Campaign}}</ref>\n\n=== Power relations in local government ===\n[[File:1957 Mao Zedong on airplane.jpg|thumb|upright=1.1|left|[[Mao Zedong]] on an airplane, 1957]]\n\nLocal governments had just as much, if not more, influence on the famine than did agriculture and higher forms of government. As the Great Leap Forward progressed, many provincial leaders began to extend their reach by working closely with Mao and higher Party leaders; which, in turn resulted in these provincial leaders abusing power that they did not actually have.<ref>{{cite book|author=Dali L. Yang|title=Calamity and Reform in China: State, Rural Society, and Institutional Change Since the Great Leap Famine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VmLuoAkMKrkC|year=1996|publisher=Stanford University Press|isbn=978-0-8047-3470-7|page=31}}</ref> This abuse of power caused passivity on the local level.  Local landlords began \"denouncing any opposition as 'conservative rightism,'\" which is defined broadly as anything anti-communist.<ref>{{cite book|author=Frank Dik\u00f6tter|title=Mao's Great Famine: The History of China's Most Devastating Catastrophe, 1958\u20131962|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5NsMWCHDStQC|date=1 October 2010|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|isbn=978-0-8027-7928-1|page=2}}</ref> With the ongoing conspiratorial theories revolving around peasants, it was seen that saving extra grain for a family to eat, the belief that the Great Leap Forward should not be implemented, or merely not working hard enough could all be seen as forms of 'conservative rightism.' This hatred led to peasants becoming unable to openly speak on collectivization and state grain purchase. By enforcing such passivity at a local level while there already was passivity at an official level, speaking and acting against the famine became a seemingly impossible task.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Kimberley Ens Manning|author2=Felix Wemheuer|title=Eating Bitterness: New Perspectives on China's Great Leap Forward and Famine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aHPTn2Rq9IUC|date=1 January 2011|publisher=UBC Press|isbn=978-0-7748-5955-4|page=110|chapter=\"The Grain Problem is an Ideological Problem\" : Discourses of Hunger in the 1957 Socialist Education Campaign}}</ref>\n\nThe influence of local government in the famine can be seen in the comparison between the provinces of Anhui and Jiangxi. Anhui, having a radical pro-Mao government, was led by [[Zeng Xisheng]] who was \"dictatorial\" with ties to Mao.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Kimberley Ens Manning|author2=Felix Wemheuer|title=Eating Bitterness: New Perspectives on China's Great Leap Forward and Famine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aHPTn2Rq9IUC|date=1 January 2011|publisher=UBC Press|isbn=978-0-7748-5955-4|pages=212\u2013213|chapter=Under the Same Maoist Sky : Accounting for Death Rate Discrepancies in Anhui and Jiangxi}}</ref> Zeng firmly believed in the Great Leap Forward and tried to hold relationships with higher officials rather than keep close local ties. Zeng proposed agricultural projects without consulting colleagues which caused Anhui's agriculture to fail terribly.  Zhang Kaifan, a party secretary and deputy-governor of the province, heard rumours of a famine breaking out in Anhui and disagreed with many of Zeng's policies. Zeng reported Zhang to Mao for such speculations which led Mao to label Zhang \"a member of the 'Peng Dehuai anti-Party military clique,'\" resulting in him being purged from the local party. Zeng was unable to report of the famine when it became an emergency situation as this would prove his hypocrisy and caused him to become a \"blatant political radical who almost single-handedly damaged Anhui.\"<ref>{{cite book|author1=Kimberley Ens Manning|author2=Felix Wemheuer|title=Eating Bitterness: New Perspectives on China's Great Leap Forward and Famine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aHPTn2Rq9IUC|date=1 January 2011|publisher=UBC Press|isbn=978-0-7748-5955-4|pages=213|chapter=Under the Same Maoist Sky : Accounting for Death Rate Discrepancies in Anhui and Jiangxi}}</ref>\n\nJiangxi encountered a situation almost opposite to that of Anhui. The leaders of Jiangxi publicly opposed some of the Great Leap programs, quietly made themselves unavailable, and even appeared to take a passive attitude towards the Maoist economy. As the leaders worked collaboratively among themselves, they also worked with the local population as well. By being able to create an environment in which the Great Leap Forward did not become fully implemented, the Jiangxi government \"did their best to minimize damage\u2026\" These findings concluded that much of the severity of the famine came down to provincial leaders and their responsibility for their regions.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Kimberley Ens Manning|author2=Felix Wemheuer|title=Eating Bitterness: New Perspectives on China's Great Leap Forward and Famine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aHPTn2Rq9IUC|date=1 January 2011|publisher=UBC Press|isbn=978-0-7748-5955-4|pages=216\u2013218|chapter=Under the Same Maoist Sky : Accounting for Death Rate Discrepancies in Anhui and Jiangxi}}</ref>\n\n=== Natural disasters ===\nIn 1960, at least some degree of drought and other bad weather affected 55% of cultivated land, while an estimated 60% of agricultural land in northern China received no rain at all.<ref name=\"Atimes\">{{cite news|last=Liu|first=Henry C K|url=http://www.atimes.com/atimes/China/FD01Ad04.html|title=Part 2: The Great Leap Forward not all bad|date=1 April 2004|work=[[Asia Times]] online|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050204085928/http://www.atimes.com/atimes/China/FD01Ad04.html|archive-date=4 February 2005}}</ref> The [[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]] yearbooks from 1958 to 1962 also reported abnormal weather, followed by droughts and floods based on Chinese government sources. This included {{convert|760|mm|in}} of rain in [[Hong Kong]] across five days in June 1959, part of a pattern that hit all of [[Southern China]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Fred Harding|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0h2gDLv3MOEC&pg=PA381|title=Breast Cancer: Cause, Prevention, Cure|publisher=Tekline Publishing|year=2006|isbn=978-0-9554221-0-2|page=381}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath ==\n\n=== Initial cover-ups ===\nLocal party leaders, for their part, conspired to cover up shortfalls and reassign blame in order to protect their own lives and positions.{{citation needed|reason=They did cover up shortfalls and invent numbers, but the second part of this needs a citation.|date=January 2018}}\n\nIn visits to [[Henan province]] in 1958, Mao observed what local officials claimed was increases in crop yield of one thousand to three thousand percent achieved, supposedly, in massive 24-hour pushes organized by the officials which they called \"sputnik launches\".  But the numbers were faked, and so were the fields that Mao observed, which had been carefully prepared in advance of Mao's visit by local officials, who removed shoots of grain from various fields and carefully transplanted them into a field prepared especially for Mao, which appeared to be a bumper crop.<ref name=\"becker\" />{{rp|122}}\n\nThe local officials became trapped by these sham demonstrations to Mao, and exhorted the peasants to reach unattainable goals, by \"deep ploughing and close planting\", and other techniques. This ended up making things much worse, the crop failed completely, leaving barren fields. No one was in a position to challenge Mao's ideas as incorrect, so peasants pulled out their bedding and coats into the fields, added seeds and water, and after they sprouted, buried the materials under the soil once the seedlings were high enough.<ref name=\"becker\" />{{rp|122}}\n\nIn a similar manner to the massive Soviet-created famine in Ukraine (the [[Holodomor]]), doctors were prohibited from listing \"starvation\" as a cause of death on death certificates. This kind of deception was far from uncommon; a famous [[propaganda]] picture from the famine shows Chinese children from [[Shandong]] province ostensibly standing atop a field of wheat, so densely grown that it could apparently support their weight. In reality, they were standing on a bench concealed beneath the plants, and the \"field\" was again entirely composed of individually transplanted stalks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RKNEdojrsMo|title=Mao's Great Famine|last=International School History|date=21 January 2015|accessdate=19 September 2018|via=YouTube|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181030033514/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RKNEdojrsMo|archive-date=30 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>[http://www.disasterhistory.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/Standing-on-Grain-Propaganda-1959.jpg Aforementioned propaganda photo. ]\n\n=== Reflections ===\nIn 1962, [[Liu Shaoqi]], then [[President of the People's Republic of China]], concluded after 44 days of field research in villages of [[Hunan]] that the reasons for the famine were 30% natural disaster and 70% human error.<ref>[http://cpc.people.com.cn/GB/64162/64172/85037/85039/5898093.html \u5218\u5c11\u5947\"\u4e09\u5206\u5929\u707e\uff0c\u4e03\u5206\u4eba\u7978\"\u63d0\u6cd5\u7684\u7531\u6765] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121214040606/http://cpc.people.com.cn/GB/64162/64172/85037/85039/5898093.html |date=14 December 2012 }}, Selection of the Party History (\u515a\u53f2\u535a\u91c7), 22 June 2007, Accessed Sept 1, 2018, CPC News. {{in lang|zh-Hans}}</ref>\n\n[[Amartya Sen]] puts this famine in a global context, arguing that lack of democracy is the major culprit: \"Indeed, no substantial famine has ever occurred in a democratic country\u2014no matter how poor.\" He adds that it is \"hard to imagine that anything like this could have happened in a country that goes to the polls regularly and that has an independent press. During that terrible calamity the government faced no pressure from newspapers, which were controlled, and none from opposition parties, which were absent.\"<ref name=\"Sen1999\">{{cite book|author=Amartya Kumar Sen|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Qm8HtpFHYecC|title=Development as freedom|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=1999|isbn=978-0-19-289330-7|accessdate=14 April 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140103042841/http://books.google.com/books?id=Qm8HtpFHYecC|archive-date=3 January 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> On the other hand, Sen points out that the numbers of \"excess mortality\" in India often surpass what they were in China during 1958\u20131961.<ref>Wiener, Jon. [https://books.google.com/books?id=1KiD069CPsUC&pg=PA38 \"How We Forgot the Cold War. A Historical Journey across America\"] University of California Press, 2012, p. 38.</ref> Sen argued that \"Despite the gigantic size of excess mortality in the Chinese famine, the extra mortality in India from regular deprivation in normal times vastly overshadows the former...India seems to manage to fill its cupboard with more skeletons every eight years than China put there in its years of shame.\"\n\nUntil the early 1980s, the [[Government of the People's Republic of China|Chinese government]]'s stance, reflected by the name \"Three Years of Natural Disasters\", was that the famine was largely a result of a series of natural disasters compounded by several planning errors. Researchers outside China argued that massive institutional and policy changes that accompanied the Great Leap Forward were the key factors in the famine, or at least worsened nature-induced disasters.<ref>{{cite video|title=China: A Century of Revolution|date=1997|people=Sue Williams (director), Howard Sharp (editor), [[Will Lyman]] (narrator)|publisher=WinStar Home Entertainment}}</ref><ref>{{citation|title=Encyclopedia of Population|volume=1|pages=388\u2013390|year=2003|editor-last=Demeny|editor-first=Paul|contribution=Famine in China|place=New York|publisher=Macmillan Reference|editor2-last=McNicoll|editor2-first=Geoffrey}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Northern Chinese Famine of 1876\u201379]]\n* [[Chinese famine of 1928\u201330]]\n* [[Chinese famine of 1942\u201343]]\n* [[Four Pests Campaign]]\n* [[Holodomor]]\n* [[Bengal famine of 1943]]\n* ''[[Hungry Ghosts: Mao's Secret Famine]]\n* ''[[Mao's Great Famine]]''\n* [[70,000 Character Petition]]\n* [[Mass killings under communist regimes]]\n\n== References ==\n\n=== Notes ===\n{{Notelist}}\n\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n{{refbegin}}\n* Ashton, Basil, Kenneth Hill, Alan Piazza, Robin Zeitz, \"Famine in China, 1958\u201361\", ''Population and Development Review,'' Vol. 10, No. 4. (Dec. 1984), pp.&nbsp;613\u2013645.\n* Banister, J. \"Analysis of Recent Data on the Population of China\", ''Population and Development,'' Vol. 10, No. 2, 1984.\n* {{cite book |last1=Becker |first1=Jasper |authorlink1=Jasper Becker |year=1998 |title=Hungry Ghosts: Mao's Secret Famine |publisher=[[Henry Holt and Company|Holt]] |series=A Holt paperback : history |isbn=0-8050-5668-8 |oclc=985077206 |ref=harv }}\n* Cao Shuji, \"The Deaths of China's Population and Its Contributing Factors during 1959\u20131961\". ''China's Population Science'' (Jan. 2005) (In Chinese).\n* ''China Statistical Yearbook'' (1984), edited by State Statistical Bureau. China Statistical Publishing House, 1984. pp.&nbsp;83, 141, 190.\n* ''China Statistical Yearbook'' (1991), edited by State Statistical Bureau. China Statistical Publishing House, 1991.\n* ''China Population Statistical Yearbook'' (1985), edited by State Statistical Bureau. China Statistical Bureau Publishing House, 1985.\n* [[Ansley J. Coale|Coale, Ansley J.]], ''Rapid Population Change in China, 1952\u20131982'', [[National Academy Press]], Washington, D.C., 1984.\n* [[Frank Dik\u00f6tter|Dik\u00f6tter, Frank]]. ''[[Mao's Great Famine|Mao's Great Famine: The History of China's Most Devastating Catastrophe, 1958\u201362]]''. [[Walker & Company]], 2010. {{ISBN|0-8027-7768-6}}.\n* Gao. Mobo (2007). ''Gao Village: Rural Life in Modern China''. [[University of Hawaii Press]]. {{ISBN|978-0-8248-3192-9}}.\n* Gao. Mobo (2008). ''The Battle for China's Past''. [[Pluto Press]]. {{ISBN|978-0-7453-2780-8}}.\n* Jiang Zhenghua (\u8523\u6b63\u83ef)\uff0c \"Method and Result of China Population Dynamic Estimation\", Academic Report of Xi'a University, 1986(3). pp.&nbsp;46, 84.\n* Li Chengrui(\u674e\u6210\u745e): Population Change Caused by The Great Leap Movement, Demographic Study, No.1, 1998 pp.&nbsp;97\u2013111\n* Li. Minqi (2008). ''The Rise of China and the Demise of the Capitalist World Economy''. [[Monthly Review Press]]. {{ISBN|978-1-58367-182-5}}\n* Peng Xizhe, \"Demographic Consequences of the Great Leap Forward in China's Provinces\", ''Population and Development Review,'' Vol. 13, No. 4. (Dec. 1987), pp.&nbsp;639\u2013670\n* Thaxton. Ralph A. Jr (2008). ''Catastrophe and Contention in Rural China: Mao's Great Leap Forward Famine and the Origins of Righteous Resistance in Da Fo Village''. [[Cambridge University Press]]. {{ISBN|0-521-72230-6}}\n* Yang, Dali. ''Calamity and Reform in China: State, Rural Society and Institutional Change since the Great Leap Famine''. Stanford University Press, 1996.\n* [[Yang Jisheng (historian)|Yang Jisheng]]. ''Tombstone (Mu Bei&nbsp;\u2013 Zhong Guo Liu Shi Nian Dai Da Ji Huang Ji Shi).'' Cosmos Books (Tian Di Tu Shu), [[Hong Kong]] 2008.\n* [[Yang Jisheng (historian)|Yang Jisheng]]. \"Tombstone: An Account of Chinese Famine in the 1960s\" (\u5893\u7891 \uff0d \u4e2d\u570b\u516d\u5341\u5e74\u4ee3\u5927\u9951\u8352\u7d00\u5be6 (Mubei \u2013 Zhongguo Liushi Niandai Da Jihuang Jishi), Hong Kong: Cosmos Books (Tiandi Tushu), 2008, {{ISBN|978-988-211-909-3}} {{in lang|zh}}. By 2010, it was appearing under the title: \u5893\u7891: \u4e00\u4e5d\u4e94\u516b-\u4e00\u4e5d\u516d\u4e8c\u5e74\u4e2d\u570b\u5927\u9951\u8352\u7d00\u5be6 (Mubei: Yi Jiu Wu Ba \u2013 Yi Jiu Liu Er Nian Zhongguo Da Jihuang Shiji) (\"Tombstone: An Account of Chinese Famine From 1958\u20131962\").\n* [[Yang Jisheng (historian)|Yang Jisheng]]. Tombstone: The Untold Story of Mao's Great Famine, Yang Jisheng, Translators: Stacy Mosher, Guo Jian, Publisher: Allen Lane (30 October 2012), {{ISBN|978-184-614-518-6}} (English translation of the above work)\n** Translated into English and abridged. Yang Jisheng, ''Tombstone: The Great Chinese Famine, 1958\u20131962'', Farrar, Straus and Giroux (30 October 2012), hardcover, 656 pp., {{ISBN|0374277931}}, {{ISBN|978-0374277932}}\n* Official Chinese statistics, shown as a graph. {{citation|url=http://www.iiasa.ac.at/Research/LUC/ChinaFood/data/pop/pop_10.htm |publisher=[[International Institute for Applied Systems Analysis]] (IIASA) |work=Land Use Systems Group (LUC)|location=[[Austria]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050904001002/http://www.iiasa.ac.at/Research/LUC/ChinaFood/data/pop/pop_10.htm |archivedate=4 September 2005|title=Data \u2013 Population Growth}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Portal bar|1950s|1960s|China}}\n\n[[Category:1959 disasters]]\n[[Category:1959 in China]]\n[[Category:1960 disasters]]\n[[Category:1960 in China]]\n[[Category:1961 disasters]]\n[[Category:1961 in China]]\n[[Category:Famines in China]]\n[[Category:Incidents of cannibalism]]\n[[Category:Man-made disasters in China]]\n", "name_user": "SCreditC", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePeople's commune", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Great_Chinese_Famine"}
{"title_page": "Kansas City, Kansas Public Library", "text_new": "{{for|the library in Missouri|Kansas City Public Library}}\n{{Infobox library\n| library_name = Kansas City, Kansas Public Library (KCKPL)\n| library_logo = File:Kansas_City,_Kansas_Public_Library_logo.png\n| location = [[Kansas City, Kansas]]\n| established = \n| num_branches = 5\n| collection_size = 368,888<ref name=\"libtech\">{{cite web | title=Kansas City Public Library | work=libraries.org | url=https://librarytechnology.org/library/1139 | accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n| annual_circulation = 1,074,126<ref name=\"libtech\"/>\n| pop_served = 150,884<ref name=\"libtech\"/>\n| budget = \n| director = Carol Levers<ref name=\"libtech\"/>\n| num_employees = \n| website = https://kckpl.org/\n}}\n'''Kansas City, Kansas Public Library''' ('''KCKPL''') is the public library system of [[Kansas City, Kansas]], headquartered in the Main Library.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20030601123836/http://www.kckpl.lib.ks.us/locate.htm|title=Locations|publisher=Kansas City, Kansas Public Library|date=2003-06-01|accessdate=2020-04-19|quote=Administration Office 625 Minnesota Ave. Kansas City, KS 66101}}</ref> The [[Kansas City Kansas Public Schools]] Board of Education controls the library system.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kckpl.org/libraries/|title=Hours & Locations|publisher=Kansas City, Kansas Public Library|accessdate=2020-04-19|quote=Main Library [...] Location: 625 Minnesota Ave., Kansas City, KS 66101[...]KCKPL is governed by the Kansas City Kansas Public Schools (USD #500) Board of Education.}}</ref>\n\n==Branches==\n[[File:Kansas City, Kansas Public Library.jpg|thumb|Postcard of the main library]]\n[[File:Argentine Carnegie Library.jpg|thumb|[[Argentine Carnegie Library]] in [[Argentine, Kansas|Argentine]]]]\nThe library system consists of five branches.\n*Main Library\n*Mr. and Mrs. F.L. Schlagle Library at [[Wyandotte County]] Lake Park - It opened on June 26, 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20011120202243/http://www.kckpl.lib.ks.us/schlagle/index.htm|title=Mr. and Mrs. F.L. Schlagle Library|publisher=Kansas City, Kansas Public Library|date=2001-11-12|accessdate=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n*South Branch Library in [[Argentine, Kansas|Argentine]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kckpl.org/libraries/south.html|title=South Branch Library|publisher=Kansas City, Kansas Library|accessdate=2020-04-18|quote=The South Branch Library is located in Kansas City, Kansas's Argentine Neighborhood[...]}}</ref> with {{convert|21000|sqft|sqm}} of space.  It opened in 2012. The name was chosen to reflect that it serves the entire southern region of the city and not a single neighborhood.<ref name=Bormann>{{cite web|author=Bormann, Dawn|url=https://www.kansascity.com/news/local/article308879/Argentine-residents-ready-to-unveil-a-new-library.html|title=Argentine residents ready to unveil a new library |work=[[Kansas City Star]]|date=2012-09-26|accessdate=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n*Turner Community Library\n*West Wyandotte Library\n\n==History==\nIt formerly operated the [[Argentine Carnegie Library]] which opened in 1911 in a storefront and received its own Carnegie building in 1917.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.archive.org/web/19980129112912/http://www.kckpl.lib.ks.us/argintro.htm|title=Argentine|publisher=Kansas City, Kansas Public Library|date=1998-01-29|accessdate=2020-04-18}}</ref> By 1998 it, on the [[National Register of Historic Places]], was the sole remaining Carnegie library in the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.archive.org/web/19980702072231/http://www.kckpl.lib.ks.us/argpage/arghome.htm|title=Argentine|publisher=Kansas City, Kansas Public Library|date=1998-07-02|accessdate=2020-04-18}}</ref> In 2012 the current South Branch opened at a cost of $6 million, one third of which was acquired by the fundraisers of local residents. The school district agreed to pay for the rest if residents raised $1.5 million to $2 million. A church was demolished to make way for the current library, and the school district took possession of the former library.<ref name=Bormann/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://kckpl.org/}}\n* {{facebook|kckpubliclibrary}}\n* {{twitter|KCKPL}}\n* {{webarchive|url=http://web.archive.org/*/http://www.kckpl.lib.ks.us/|title=Kansas City, Kansas Public Library (kckpl.lib.ks.us)}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Public libraries in Kansas]]\n[[Category:Education in Kansas City, Kansas]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the library in Missouri|Kansas City Public Library}}\n{{Infobox library\n| library_name = Kansas City, Kansas Public Library (KCKPL)\n| library_logo = File:Kansas_City,_Kansas_Public_Library_logo.png\n| location = [[Kansas City, Kansas]]\n| established = \n| num_branches = 5\n| collection_size = 368,888<ref name=\"libtech\">{{cite web | title=Kansas City Public Library | work=libraries.org | url=https://librarytechnology.org/library/1139 | accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n| annual_circulation = 1,074,126<ref name=\"libtech\"/>\n| pop_served = 150,884<ref name=\"libtech\"/>\n| budget = \n| director = Carol Levers<ref name=\"libtech\"/>\n| num_employees = \n| website = https://kckpl.org/\n}}\n'''Kansas City, Kansas Public Library''' ('''KCKPL''') is the public library system of [[Kansas City, Kansas]], headquartered in the Main Library.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20030601123836/http://www.kckpl.lib.ks.us/locate.htm|title=Locations|publisher=Kansas City, Kansas Public Library|date=2003-06-01|accessdate=2020-04-19|quote=Administration Office 625 Minnesota Ave. Kansas City, KS 66101}}</ref> The [[Kansas City Kansas Public Schools]] Board of Education controls the library system.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kckpl.org/libraries/|title=Hours & Locations|publisher=Kansas City, Kansas Public Library|accessdate=2020-04-19|quote=Main Library [...] Location: 625 Minnesota Ave., Kansas City, KS 66101[...]KCKPL is governed by the Kansas City Kansas Public Schools (USD #500) Board of Education.}}</ref>\n\n==Branches==\n[[File:Kansas City, Kansas Public Library.jpg|thumb|Postcard of the main library]]\n[[File:Argentine Carnegie Library.jpg|thumb|[[Argentine Carnegie Library]] in [[Argentine, Kansas|Argentine]]]]\nThe library system consists of five branches.\n*Main Library\n*Mr. and Mrs. F.L. Schlagle Library at [[Wyandotte County]] Lake Park - It opened on June 26, 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20011120202243/http://www.kckpl.lib.ks.us/schlagle/index.htm|title=Mr. and Mrs. F.L. Schlagle Library|publisher=Kansas City, Kansas Public Library|date=2001-11-12|accessdate=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n*South Branch Library in [[Argentine, Kansas|Argentine]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kckpl.org/libraries/south.html|title=South Branch Library|publisher=Kansas City, Kansas Library|accessdate=2020-04-18|quote=The South Branch Library is located in Kansas City, Kansas's Argentine Neighborhood[...]}}</ref> with {{convert|21000|sqft|sqm}} of space.  It opened in 2012. The name was chosen to reflect that it serves the entire southern region of the city and not a single neighborhood.<ref name=Bormann>{{cite web|author=Bormann, Dawn|url=https://www.kansascity.com/news/local/article308879/Argentine-residents-ready-to-unveil-a-new-library.html|title=Argentine residents ready to unveil a new library |work=[[Kansas City Star]]|date=2012-09-26|accessdate=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n*Turner Community Library\n*West Wyandotte Library\n\n==History==\nIt formerly operated the [[Argentine Carnegie Library]] which opened in 1911 in a storefront and received its own Carnegie building in 1917.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.archive.org/web/19980129112912/http://www.kckpl.lib.ks.us/argintro.htm|title=Argentine|publisher=Kansas City, Kansas Public Library|date=1998-01-29|accessdate=2020-04-18}}</ref> By 1998 it, on the [[National Register of Historic Places]], was the sole remaining Carnegie library in the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.archive.org/web/19980702072231/http://www.kckpl.lib.ks.us/argpage/arghome.htm|title=Argentine|publisher=Kansas City, Kansas Public Library|date=1998-07-02|accessdate=2020-04-18}}</ref> In 2012 the current South Branch opened at a cost of $6 million, one third of which was acquired by the fundraisers of local residents. The school district agreed to pay for the rest if residents raised $1.5 million to $2 million. A church was demolished to make way for the current library, and the school district took possession of the former library.<ref name=Bormann/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://kckpl.org/}}\n* {{facebook|kckpubliclibrary}}\n* {{twitter|KCKPL}}\n* {{webarchive|url=http://web.archive.org/*/http://www.kckpl.lib.ks.us/|title=Kansas City, Kansas Public Library (kckpl.lib.ks.us)}}\n[[Category:Public libraries in Kansas]]\n[[Category:Education in Kansas City, Kansas]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kansas_City,_Kansas_Public_Library"}
